<div class="policy-family" id="fam-jus">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">JUS</span>
<span class="family-title">POL: Police Use of Force and Weaponry</span>
<span class="family-count">0/2 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="JUST-POLC-0006">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">JUST-POLC-0006</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Ban police automatic weapons</p><p class="rule-plain">Police departments should not possess or deploy automatic weapons, military machine guns capable of sustained automatic fire, in routine law enforcement operations. Automatic weapons are designed for military combat, not community policing, and their deployment escalates violence and damages public trust.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Law enforcement agencies at all levels of government are prohibited from acquiring, possessing, or deploying fully automatic weapons in routine policing operations; federally certified specialized tactical units (SWAT, counter-terrorism, hostage rescue) may possess such weapons only under documented individualized authorization, strict inventory accountability, and federal oversight; deployment in crowd control, protest response, or routine patrol is prohibited without exception.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">This rule prohibits police departments from possessing or deploying automatic weapons in routine policing operations. Automatic weapons (machine guns, assault rifles capable of sustained automatic fire) are designed for military combat, not law enforcement. Their use escalates violence, undermines de-escalation principles, and militarizes police-community relations. Specialized tactical units may require access to specific weapons for high-risk situations (active shooter response, hostage rescue, counter-terrorism operations), but these should be strictly limited, subject to oversight, and not part of general patrol equipment. The militarization of routine policing has transformed police departments into occupying forces in many communities, particularly communities of color. Banning automatic weapons for police is part of a broader de-militarization and accountability framework. This rule does not disarm police, it limits them to weapons appropriate for law enforcement rather than military combat. Standard service pistols, shotguns, and precision rifles for specialized situations remain available. The goal is to prevent the arms-race dynamic where police militarization drives civilian armament and vice versa. Gap: The line between "routine policing" and "specialized tactical operations" is contested and will be drawn by agencies seeking to preserve capability; the exception for specialized units must require individualized federal authorization and public transparency reports, not self-certification by the department. Loophole: Departments could reclassify general patrol functions as "specialized" to retain automatic weapons while nominally complying with the prohibition on routine deployment; independent federal authorization for each tactical unit prevents self-classification evasion. Abuse path: Automatic weapons could be selectively deployed against specific communities, political protesters, minority communities, under a "specialized" designation; oversight and deployment logs must be public and subject to civil rights audit. Unintended consequence: De-militarization of police may be reversed by subsequent administrations through administrative action unless codified by statute rather than implemented by executive order. [VERIFY: 18 U.S.C. § 922(o) restricts civilian automatic weapon transfers but exempts government agencies; statutory prohibition on law enforcement acquisition would be a separate enactment.]</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="JUST-POLC-0007">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">JUST-POLC-0007</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Ban police weapons of war</p><p class="rule-plain">Police departments must not possess military combat equipment, armored personnel carriers, grenade launchers, armed drones, and similar weapons of war. Equipment designed for combat against enemy combatants is not appropriate for policing American communities and its presence militarizes law enforcement, escalates violence, and erodes civil liberties.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Federal law must prohibit law enforcement agencies from acquiring, retaining, or deploying weapons and equipment designed for military combat that serve no legitimate law enforcement purpose, including: armored personnel carriers and military-specification combat vehicles; grenade launchers and explosive projectile weapons; bayonets; armed unmanned aerial vehicles; and military-specification area-denial systems; the Department of Defense 1033 Program’s transfer of such equipment to civilian law enforcement is prohibited; existing inventory of prohibited equipment must be returned to federal custody or destroyed within 18 months of enactment.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">This rule extends beyond automatic weapons to prohibit police possession of any weapons designed for military combat rather than law enforcement. This includes: - Armored personnel carriers and military-grade vehicles (MRAPs, tanks) - Grenade launchers and explosive devices - Bayonets and other military combat weapons - Military-grade body armor and tactical gear designed for combat rather than protection - Surveillance and weapons systems designed for warfare (armed drones, military-grade surveillance equipment) The 1033 Program has transferred billions of dollars of surplus military equipment to local police departments, transforming law enforcement into a paramilitary force. This equipment is not designed for community policing, de-escalation, or public safety, it is designed for combat operations against enemy combatants. Its presence in policing escalates violence, undermines trust, and creates a mentality where communities are viewed as battlegrounds rather than neighborhoods to protect. Exceptions may be necessary for specialized federal units dealing with terrorism or organized crime, but these should be strictly limited, transparent, and subject to oversight. General municipal and county police departments should not possess weapons of war. This rule addresses the root cause of police violence: when police are equipped like soldiers, they act like soldiers. De-militarization is a prerequisite for accountability, de-escalation, and community trust. Gap: The 1033 Program operates through DoD administrative action; a statutory prohibition is required to prevent circumvention through program rebranding or renewal. Loophole: Local law enforcement agencies that receive prohibited equipment from private donors rather than through 1033 are not covered by a 1033 ban alone; the prohibition must apply to acquisition regardless of source. Abuse path: Federal agencies could maintain prohibited equipment under "federal partnership" arrangements with local departments, retaining nominal federal ownership while making equipment available for local deployment; the prohibition must cover constructive availability as well as formal transfer. Unintended consequence: Some specialized federal law enforcement agencies (FBI, ATF, DEA) may require certain tactical equipment for operations against organized crime and terrorism; the prohibition should be structured to apply to general municipal police departments while preserving narrowly tailored federal law enforcement capability with strict authorization requirements. [VERIFY: Constitutional analysis under Posse Comitatus Act context and applicable statutory authority for 1033 reform.]</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-gun-reg">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">GUN</span>
<span class="family-title">REG: General Firearm Regulation Authority</span>
<span class="family-count">0/2 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-REGS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-REGS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Constitutional authority to regulate firearms</p>
<p class="rule-plain">A constitutional amendment must clarify that the Second Amendment does not prevent reasonable gun safety regulations. Without this, courts may continue striking down public safety laws based on increasingly narrow readings of the right to bear arms.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Amend the Constitution to explicitly affirm government authority to regulate firearms and weaponry</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The Second Amendment's text has generated two centuries of interpretive conflict, most recently crystallized in <em>Bruen</em> (2022), which requires gun regulations to satisfy a "history and tradition" test that effectively immunizes modern safety laws from modern evidence. A targeted constitutional amendment explicitly affirming Congress's and states' authority to regulate firearms and weaponry would provide stable legal ground for the rest of this policy area, background checks, weapons-of-war bans, training requirements, and militia accountability, without requiring each rule to survive judicial second-guessing. The <em>Bruen</em> test’s structural problem is that it requires 21st-century regulations to find 18th-century regulatory analogues for weapons and circumstances with no founding-era analog: there were no AR-15s, no semi-automatic pistols, no ghost guns, and no 30-round magazines in 1791. Lower courts applying <em>Bruen</em> have struck down regulations on ghost guns, bump stocks, domestic violence disarmament, and carrying in sensitive places, generating a circuit split on foundational public safety laws (Ruben & Blocher, 2023). Gap: A constitutional amendment is the most durable solution but requires two-thirds of Congress and three-fourths of states, the most politically difficult path; near-term legislative action must proceed in parallel with amendment advocacy rather than waiting for amendment ratification. Loophole: Congress can address <em>Bruen</em> on its own terms by passing gun safety statutes with detailed historical findings sections documenting the extensive founding-era tradition of firearm regulation; the gun industry has systematically suppressed this historical record in litigation, and Congress must compile and present it. Abuse path: A Court majority hostile to gun regulation could apply <em>Bruen</em> so narrowly that even a comprehensive statutory findings record is dismissed as insufficient; the constitutional amendment is therefore not a fallback but the primary long-term structural remedy. Unintended consequence: Pursuing a constitutional amendment may generate a political backlash that delays near-term reform if not paired with concrete near-term legislative action.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-REGS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-REGS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Congress must respond legislatively to <em>Bruen</em>'s "historical tradition" test to preserve the constitutional viability of modern gun safety regulations</p>
<p class="rule-plain">A 2022 Supreme Court ruling said gun laws must match 'historical tradition' from 1791, making many modern safety measures vulnerable to legal challenge. Congress must pass a statutory foundation so public safety rules can withstand court review.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Congress must respond to <em>Bruen</em> on multiple tracks simultaneously: (a) enact gun safety legislation in mandatory, unambiguous terms -- eliminating the discretionary language courts exploit to void regulations; (b) include in every gun safety bill a detailed historical findings section documenting the founding-era tradition of firearm regulation -- extensive colonial and early-republic regulation of storage, carry, and unsafe use must be compiled and presented on <em>Bruen</em>'s own evidentiary terms; (c) fund the compilation, digitization, and preservation of a comprehensive historical record of colonial and early-republic firearm regulation for use in federal judicial proceedings; (d) pursue a constitutional amendment explicitly clarifying that the Second Amendment permits reasonable public safety regulations enacted on the basis of contemporary evidence of harm, and that the constitutional test for such regulations is not limited to finding analogues in the regulatory practice of a pre-industrial society.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: New York State Rifle &amp; Pistol Association, Inc. v. Bruen, 597 U.S. 1 (2022) (replacing two-step means-ends scrutiny with "history and tradition" test); United States v. Rahimi, 602 U.S. ___ (2024) (clarifying historical analogues need not be precise -- modest correction leaving the structural problem intact); Bevis v. City of Naperville, 85 F.4th 1175 (7th Cir. 2023) (upholding Illinois assault weapons ban under Bruen); Bianchi v. Brown (4th Cir. 2024) (striking down Maryland ban -- circuit split indicating Supreme Court review is likely); U.S. Const. amend. II. Empirical evidence: Courts applying Bruen have struck down ghost gun regulations, domestic violence disarmament provisions, and sensitive-places restrictions -- generating a circuit split on foundational public safety laws (Ruben &amp; Blocher, 2023, California Law Review); the historical record of colonial and early-republic firearm regulation is extensive but has been systematically suppressed in gun industry litigation (Cornell &amp; DeDino, 2004, Fordham Law Review); Rahimi offered a modest clarification but left the structural problem of forcing 21st-century safety laws through an 18th-century evidentiary framework intact. Enforcement mechanisms: Mandatory unambiguous statutory language -- removes interpretive gaps courts exploit; historical findings sections -- satisfies Bruen on its own evidentiary terms; federal historical record compilation -- prevents the gun industry from winning by default in the historical record; constitutional amendment as long-term structural remedy. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (mandatory statutory language -- removes interpretive gaps); KERN-0004 (constitutional amendment requires broad democratic authorization); KERN-0009 (preserves government's ability to protect public safety against gun violence); ENFA-0001 (eliminating discretionary language is an enforcement mechanism). Adversarial review: Gap -- the rule focuses on preserving regulatory authority but does not require any specific safety legislation; Congress could satisfy these requirements while enacting weak laws; this rule must be paired with the substantive requirements in other families (BANS, LICS, STWS, SAFE, TRAF, EXCL). Loophole -- a congressional historical findings section can be compiled and presented to courts but cannot compel courts to accept it; the Supreme Court's Bruen majority has shown willingness to dismiss historical evidence that does not satisfy its preferred narrative; the constitutional amendment is not an optional alternative but the required long-term solution. Unintended consequence -- pursuing a constitutional amendment may mobilize gun-rights groups in ways that make the near-term legislative agenda harder to advance; amendment advocacy must run in parallel with near-term legislation, not as a substitute. Abuse path -- a bad-faith Congress could frame gun safety laws in absolutist terms that guarantee constitutional challenge, deliberately creating losing litigation to establish precedent rolling back the remaining regulatory floor.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-gun-ban">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">GUN</span>
<span class="family-title">BAN: Prohibited Weapons and Ownership</span>
<span class="family-count">0/4 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-BANS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-BANS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Ban weapons of war from civilian ownership</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Private citizens should not own weapons built for military combat, including both fully automatic firearms and semi-automatic versions engineered to work around bans. These weapons have no civilian hunting or self-defense purpose that justifies the risk.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Ban private ownership of weapons of war including automatic weapons and semi-automatic military analogues designed to evade regulation</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Automatic weapons have been federally restricted since the National Firearms Act (1934) and effectively banned for new civilian manufacture since 1986. This rule extends that principle to semi-automatic military analogues, AR-15 and AK-47 variants, designed to maximize lethality in sustained combat. These weapons offer no legitimate civilian use that a standard semi-automatic hunting rifle or handgun cannot serve. Their defining characteristic is combat optimization: high-capacity magazines, rapid fire, and ergonomic design for sustained shooting. <em>Bruen</em> challenge risk: An assault weapons ban faces significant constitutional challenge, the government would need to demonstrate a historical tradition of regulating military-style weapons for civilian use; the Seventh Circuit upheld Illinois’s assault weapons ban in <em>Bevis v. City of Naperville</em> (2023), but the Fourth Circuit in <em>Bianchi v. Brown</em> reached the opposite conclusion for Maryland’s ban, a circuit split indicating Supreme Court review is likely. Gap: "Weapons of war" must be defined by statute with sufficient precision to survive constitutional vagueness challenge; the definition cannot simply list named models (manufacturers adapt) but must define functional and design categories. Loophole: The manufacturing prohibition does not immediately address the estimated 20+ million AR-style rifles already in civilian hands; a buyback program (per GUNS-BANS-0004) is the companion policy. Unintended consequence: A ban on new manufacture that exempts existing stock creates two-tier ownership dynamics and may increase the market value of grandfathered weapons, perversely incentivizing accumulation before a ban takes effect.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-BANS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-BANS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Evasion-resistant definition of weapons of war</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Any ban on weapons of war must use a definition that gun manufacturers can't sidestep with small design tweaks. The law must cover the full category of military-style firearms, not just specific named models.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Definition of weapons of war must be evasion-resistant and cover both automatic weapons and demilitarized semi-automatic civilian versions</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Without an evasion-resistant statutory definition, manufacturers can circumvent bans through minor mechanical modifications, removing a third-position selector, for example, while producing functionally equivalent weapons. The definition must address design intent and lethality optimization rather than mechanical configuration alone. A weapons-of-war definition that is not evasion-resistant is no definition at all; industry will exploit any gap. The 1994 federal assault weapons ban’s feature-based definition was immediately circumvented by manufacturers who removed listed cosmetic features while retaining the same firing mechanism, caliber, and magazine capacity, producing functionally equivalent "California compliant" configurations. Gap: An "evasion-resistant" definition that relies on subjective assessments of "design intent" may create enforcement unpredictability and vagueness challenges; the statute should combine objective functional criteria (fire rate capability, caliber, magazine compatibility) with a delegation to ATF to designate additional configurations meeting the functional definition without requiring new congressional action. Loophole: Manufacturers create product lines with minor variations specifically designed to fall outside each new regulatory definition; the ATF designation authority must include explicit power to cover functional equivalents proactively. Unintended consequence: An overbroad definition could capture standard hunting and sporting rifles; the definition must be calibrated to the specific lethality characteristics of weapons-of-war without sweeping in mainstream lawful civilian firearms.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-BANS-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-BANS-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Ban high-capacity ammunition magazines</p>
<p class="rule-plain">High-capacity magazines: attachments that let a shooter fire many rounds without reloading, must be banned above a set limit. Fewer shots before reloading means more chances for people to escape or for others to intervene.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Ban high-capacity ammunition magazines above a defined threshold</p>
<p class="rule-notes">High-capacity magazines allow shooters to fire more rounds without reloading, directly increasing the body count in mass shootings. Research has found significant reductions in high-fatality mass shootings in states that enacted large-capacity magazine bans. The threshold, commonly set at 10 rounds, must be defined in statute. Existing magazines should be subject to grandfathering provisions tied to surrender or modification programs, with meaningful enforcement mechanisms rather than unenforceable paper bans. Research by Klarevas, Conner, and Hemenway (2019) found that mass shootings using large-capacity magazines resulted in 98% more deaths and 157% more injuries than attacks without them.<sup><a href="#fn1" id="ref1b">[1]</a></sup> <em>Bruen</em> challenge risk: Magazine capacity limits face challenge under the <em>Bruen</em> test; the Third and Fourth Circuits have split on this, and the Ninth Circuit upheld California’s ban en banc in <em>Duncan v. Bonta</em>; a comprehensive historical findings record documenting colonial-era restrictions on weaponry is the preferred litigation strategy. Gap: Grandfathered existing high-capacity magazines, numbering in the tens of millions, cannot be eliminated without a buyback or registration program; prohibition on new manufacture without a grandfathering exit path leaves the existing stock permanently unaddressed. Loophole: Magazines manufactured from two lower-capacity components that can be assembled post-prohibition could evade a ban on finished magazines; the statute must prohibit components designed for prohibited-capacity assembly as well as the assembled magazine.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-BANS-0004">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-BANS-0004</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Enact a new federal assault weapons ban with a feature-based, evasion-resistant definition and a federally funded voluntary buyback for currently owned weapons</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Congress must pass a new federal ban on assault-style weapons using a clear, feature-based definition that closes the loopholes in the 1994 law. A government-funded voluntary buyback would let people who already own these weapons sell them back.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Congress must enact a new federal assault weapons ban that: (a) defines assault weapons by functional features -- not named models -- as any semi-automatic centerfire rifle accepting a detachable magazine and incorporating a pistol grip, thumbhole stock, folding or telescoping stock, flash suppressor, or grenade launcher; and any semi-automatic pistol accepting a detachable magazine over 10 rounds; (b) delegates to ATF authority to designate additional configurations achieving functional equivalence through minor mechanical variation; (c) prohibits manufacture, importation, sale, transfer, and possession of newly manufactured qualifying weapons and magazines exceeding 10 rounds; (d) establishes a federally funded voluntary buyback at fair market value for currently owned assault weapons and high-capacity magazines, funded through a dedicated excise tax surcharge on new firearms and ammunition; (e) grandfathers existing lawfully owned weapons only upon completion of federal registration and an enhanced background check within 18 months of enactment -- unregistered weapons are contraband subject to forfeiture after that deadline.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: Public Safety and Recreational Firearms Use Protection Act, Pub. L. 103-322, §§ 110101-110106 (1994 federal assault weapons ban, expired 2004); National Firearms Act, 26 U.S.C. §§ 5801-5872 (existing automatic weapons regulatory framework since 1934); Gun Control Act of 1968, 18 U.S.C. §§ 921-931 (licensing and manufacturing framework); New York State Rifle &amp; Pistol Association, Inc. v. Bruen, 597 U.S. 1 (2022) (constitutional framework requiring historical tradition showing); Bevis v. City of Naperville, 85 F.4th 1175 (7th Cir. 2023) (upholding assault weapons ban under Bruen); Bianchi v. Brown (4th Cir. 2024) (striking down Maryland ban -- circuit split requiring Supreme Court resolution). Empirical evidence: DiMaggio et al. (2019), Journal of Trauma and Acute Care Surgery, found mass shooting deaths were significantly lower during the 1994-2004 ban period and increased substantially following expiration; the 1994 ban's feature-based definition was immediately circumvented by manufacturers producing functionally identical "California compliant" configurations; approximately 20 million AR-style rifles are estimated to be in civilian circulation (Small Arms Survey data). Enforcement mechanisms: Federal registration with 18-month deadline -- creates contraband classification for unregistered weapons after deadline; ATF designation authority -- closes evasion gaps via minor mechanical variation without new legislation; dedicated excise tax funding -- ensures the buyback is funded without annual appropriations vulnerability; forfeiture after deadline -- enforcement mechanism for post-deadline possession. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (statutory ban with federal registration survives executive non-enforcement); KERN-0004 (voluntary buyback -- no mandatory confiscation); KERN-0009 (weapons-of-war ban directly protects public safety against mass casualty attacks); ECON-0002 (dedicated excise tax is self-sustaining); ENFA-0001 (forfeiture after deadline and ATF designation authority are enforcement mechanisms). Adversarial review: Gap -- the 18-month registration window requires owners to actively register; enforcement against non-compliance in a pool of approximately 20 million rifles is practically very difficult without broader firearms registration infrastructure; the mandate must be paired with realistic ATF staffing. Loophole -- the ATF designation authority for "functional equivalents" creates administrative law challenge risk; gun manufacturers will litigate each ATF designation; a statutory backstop defining prohibited functional equivalence categories is needed to reduce reliance on the ATF mechanism. Unintended consequence -- a voluntary buyback at "fair market value" may not incentivize high-value collectors or principled resisters; after-deadline forfeiture creates the political controversy of government confiscation even though it applies only to weapons never registered. Abuse path -- a hostile administration could underfund the ATF designation process and buyback program; the mandatory excise tax funding mechanism must be written so appropriators cannot redirect it to other purposes.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-gun-acq">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">GUN</span>
<span class="family-title">ACQ: Acquisition and Background Checks</span>
<span class="family-count">0/3 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-ACQS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-ACQS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Universal background checks for all acquisitions</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Before anyone can buy a gun, they must pass a background check, a screening process that flags people legally barred from owning firearms. This already applies to licensed dealers but must extend to every purchase.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Require background checks for all firearm acquisitions</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Federal law currently requires background checks only for purchases from federally licensed dealers. Private sales, gun show transactions, and informal transfers between individuals are exempt in most states, creating an enforcement gap consistently exploited by prohibited buyers. Universal background checks are supported by large majorities of Americans across party lines and represent the most foundational element of any serious gun safety framework. Approximately 22% of gun acquisitions occur through private sales without background checks, providing a systematic pathway for prohibited persons to obtain firearms (Kagawa et al., 2018). National polling shows approximately 89–92% public support, including among gun owners and Republican voters (Gallup, 2023). <em>Bruen</em> note: Universal background checks are among the most constitutionally secure gun regulations, there is substantial founding-era evidence of screening requirements for arms-bearing, and background check requirements have survived <em>Bruen</em> challenges in lower courts. Gap: Background checks screen for prior disqualifying records but not for individuals who have not yet been formally adjudicated dangerous despite warning signs; red flag laws (GUNS-RFLS-0001) address this residual gap. Loophole: Prohibited persons can still obtain firearms through straw purchases by non-prohibited proxies; enhanced straw purchase penalties (GUNS-STWS-0001) and dealer accountability rules are the complementary enforcement mechanisms. Abuse path: NICS database incompleteness, underreported disqualifying records from states and agencies, means background checks can clear prohibited purchasers; mandatory reporting requirements (GUNS-ACQS-0003) are the structural fix.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-ACQS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-ACQS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Background checks cover all transfers including private sales</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Currently, private sellers and gun-show vendors don't have to run background checks the way licensed gun stores do. This closes that loophole so every firearm transfer, including private sales, goes through the same screening process.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Background check requirement applies to all transfers including private sales and gun shows</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The private-sale exemption in the Brady Handgun Violence Prevention Act allows individuals to transfer firearms without any federal oversight. Extending the requirement to all transfers, gifts, loans, gun show sales, and online transactions, requires federal legislation and coordination with state-level enforcement. Without this extension, background checks remain only partially universal, and the gun show and private-sale loopholes remain open to exploitation. The private-sale exemption creates a structural gap: a person who fails a dealer background check can immediately acquire the same weapon through a private sale in most states. ATF trace data confirms that private sales are a significant source of crime guns in states without universal background check laws. Enforcement challenge: Universal background check laws are difficult to enforce without a firearm registration system that documents initial acquisition; without knowing who owns a specific weapon, it is impossible to verify that any transfer was preceded by a background check. Federal implementation requires either licensed dealer facilitation for all private transfers or a federal system of licensed transfer agents, the most practical enforcement model. Gap: Online platforms (Armslist and similar services) facilitate de facto private sales that are difficult to enforce universally without platform-level compliance obligations; platform liability requirements should accompany the transfer check mandate. Loophole: Sellers who facilitate private transfers without background checks face minimal federal prosecution risk under current enforcement patterns; mandatory prosecution guidelines for flagrant violations are needed to establish deterrence.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-ACQS-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-ACQS-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Comprehensive and interoperable background check databases</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Background checks are only as good as the records behind them. States and agencies must share complete, current data so that disqualifying records don't fall through the cracks.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Background check databases must be comprehensive, interoperable, and up to date</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Multiple mass shooters passed background checks because prior disqualifying records, mental health adjudications, domestic violence convictions, felony charges, had not been properly submitted to the National Instant Criminal Background Check System (NICS). Comprehensive database coverage and interoperability across all jurisdictions is a prerequisite for background checks to be effective. Record submission must be mandatory, not voluntary, for all disqualifying events. The Sutherland Springs church shooting (2017) illustrated the failure mode: the shooter’s disqualifying Air Force court-martial conviction was never reported to NICS, allowing him to pass a background check and purchase the weapon used in a mass casualty attack. The Virginia Tech shooting (2007) involved a similar database reporting failure for a mental health adjudication. Both cases were preventable with mandatory reporting. Gap: Mental health adjudication records, domestic violence protective orders, and state criminal records are the most significant underreported categories; the record submission deadline must be 48 hours maximum with meaningful federal funding penalties for jurisdictions that fail to comply. Loophole: "Adjudications" are the current standard for mental health disqualification, individuals who are clearly dangerous but have never been formally adjudicated (never hospitalized or judicially committed) fall outside database coverage; red flag laws (GUNS-RFLS-0001) address this gap through behavioral-risk criteria rather than formal adjudication requirements. Unintended consequence: Mandatory mental health reporting to a firearms disqualification database creates strong disincentives to voluntarily seek mental health treatment; the scope of reportable adjudications must be drawn narrowly to acute danger findings, not broad outpatient treatment or diagnosis.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-gun-trn">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">GUN</span>
<span class="family-title">TRN: Training and Safety Requirements</span>
<span class="family-count">0/3 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-TRAN-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-TRAN-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Mandatory safety training for firearm ownership</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Anyone who wants to own a firearm must first complete a certified safety course. Safety training teaches people how to handle, store, and operate guns properly, reducing accidents and unintentional shootings.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Require safety training as a condition of firearm ownership</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Safety training requirements, analogous to driver's license requirements, reduce accidental discharges, improve handling under stress, and establish a baseline of competence. Training does not prohibit gun ownership; it ensures owners can safely handle and store the weapons they own. Federal minimum standards should define required curriculum, qualified instructors, and certification processes. States may impose higher standards but not lower. Motor vehicle operation requires demonstrated competence as a condition of licensure, a standard that has never been seriously challenged as a constitutional barrier to car ownership. The analogy to firearm safety training is direct: both involve potentially lethal equipment whose safe operation requires specific knowledge. States that require safety training for concealed carry permits have documented lower rates of accidental discharges. Gap: Training requirements must specify curriculum, qualified instructors, and assessment standards to prevent nominally compliant but practically inadequate programs. Loophole: A person who purchases a firearm and completes training afterward has not been trained at the time of first handling, training must be certified before purchase, not retroactively. <em>Bruen</em> note: Training requirements tied to arms-bearing are supported by extensive founding-era evidence from militia drilling and proficiency requirements, making them among the more constitutionally secure regulations in this policy area.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-TRAN-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-TRAN-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Mandatory de-escalation training for ownership</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Gun owners must also complete training in de-escalation, learning how to defuse tense situations without reaching for a weapon. Most conflicts don't require lethal force, and trained gun owners make better decisions under pressure.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Require de-escalation training as a condition of firearm ownership</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The presence of a firearm in a confrontational situation frequently escalates rather than resolves the conflict. De-escalation training teaches firearm owners to recognize threatening dynamics before they become lethal, defuse tension, and avoid situations where a weapon is drawn unnecessarily. This training is particularly important given research showing that most defensive gun uses involve ambiguous situations where de-escalation was available but not employed. Gap: "De-escalation" is a term with specific clinical and law enforcement meaning that must be operationalized in training standards; a vague requirement can be satisfied by a 30-minute module that provides no practical skill. The curriculum must specify scenario-based training developed by credentialed conflict-resolution professionals. Loophole: Once trained, an owner faces no recurring training requirement unless a renewal system is established; de-escalation skills degrade without practice, suggesting that the licensing renewal cycle (GUNS-LICS-0001) should include a de-escalation refresher component. Unintended consequence: Mandatory training requirements impose costs that may fall disproportionately on lower-income gun owners; training subsidy programs should accompany the mandate to prevent differential enforcement and ensure access equity.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-TRAN-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-TRAN-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Safe storage requirement</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Federal law must require all gun owners to store their weapons securely when not in use. A national minimum standard ensures no state can opt out, and that children and unauthorized users everywhere face a locked barrier before reaching a firearm.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Require secure storage of firearms; safe storage law as federal minimum standard</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Unsecured firearms in the home are a leading source of youth gun deaths, stolen weapons diverted to crime, and accidental discharges. Safe storage requirements, requiring firearms to be stored in locked containers or with trigger locks when not in active use, are associated with significant reductions in youth firearm injuries and gun theft. A federal minimum standard ensures baseline protection nationwide and removes the patchwork of inconsistent state requirements that currently allow unsafe storage practices to persist in much of the country. Approximately 4.6 million children in the United States live in homes with loaded, unlocked guns; states with child access prevention (CAP) laws have significantly lower rates of youth gun deaths, states with strong CAP laws had 23% fewer firearm fatalities among children (Hepburn et al., 2006). Gap: Safe storage requirements are only as effective as enforcement mechanisms; a law requiring locked storage but providing no inspection authority or verified consequence is essentially aspirational. Civil liability for owners whose unsecured weapons are accessed by children or stolen and used in crimes provides an enforcement mechanism through the courts that does not depend on regulatory inspection. Loophole: The rule must specify what "secure storage" means, a cable lock through a trigger guard does not prevent access by a determined older child; standards must require locked, tamper-resistant containers for loaded firearms not in active use. <em>Bruen</em> note: Safe storage requirements have substantial founding-era analogues in powder house regulations and statutes requiring safe storage of loaded firearms in common areas; these historical analogues support constitutional viability.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-gun-mhe">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">GUN</span>
<span class="family-title">MHE: Mental Health Evaluations</span>
<span class="family-count">0/2 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-MHES-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-MHES-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Dangerousness-based mental health evaluation</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Any mental health screening for gun ownership must focus on whether someone poses a real danger, not simply whether they carry a diagnosis. Most people with mental illness are not violent, and broad exclusions would be both unfair and ineffective.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Mental health evaluations for gun ownership must be narrowly tailored to dangerousness, not diagnosis category</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The existing federal prohibition on firearm ownership by persons "adjudicated as a mental defective" is both overbroad and underinclusive, excluding non-dangerous individuals while missing dangerous ones without formal adjudication. Evaluations must focus narrowly on the specific question of imminent risk of harm to self or others, using trained professionals applying evidence-based criteria. Dangerousness, not diagnosis category, is the constitutionally and ethically appropriate standard. The research base establishes that mental illness as a category is a poor predictor of gun violence, most gun violence is committed by individuals without diagnosable mental illness, and most people with mental illness pose no elevated violence risk. A broad mental-illness criterion would stigmatize approximately 1 in 5 Americans who experience mental illness annually while failing to prevent most gun violence. Gap: "Dangerousness" is itself a clinical construct that must be operationalized through evidence-based criteria; a vague standard gives assessors subjective discretion that can be applied inconsistently across demographic groups, with well-documented disparities in how dangerousness is assessed for persons of color. Loophole: Assessments focus on formally evaluated individuals; dangerous individuals who have never been evaluated by a mental health professional will not be captured by any mental health screening system, red flag laws (GUNS-RFLS-0001) address this by providing a behavioral-indicator-based mechanism. Unintended consequence: Risk of losing gun rights is frequently cited as a reason to avoid seeking mental health care; this chilling effect on treatment-seeking worsens population mental health outcomes and may actually increase violence risk in the long term.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-MHES-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-MHES-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">No blanket exclusion based on diagnosis alone</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Having a mental health diagnosis, like depression or anxiety, cannot by itself be the reason someone is barred from owning a firearm. The law must assess actual, evidence-based risk of violence rather than stigmatizing entire groups.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Prohibit blanket exclusion from firearm ownership based solely on a mental health diagnosis</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Categorical exclusions based on diagnosis, ADHD, depression, autism, PTSD, are both discriminatory and counterproductive. The vast majority of individuals with mental health conditions pose no elevated risk of violence. Blanket diagnosis-based exclusions also discourage people from seeking mental health treatment, fearing loss of gun rights, which worsens population health outcomes without meaningfully improving safety. The criterion must be individual dangerousness assessment, not categorical diagnosis. The existing federal prohibition under 18 U.S.C. § 922(g)(4) bars firearms possession by persons "adjudicated as a mental defective" or committed to a mental institution, a category that is both overbroad (capturing non-dangerous individuals committed for voluntary treatment) and underinclusive (missing dangerous individuals who have never been formally adjudicated). Reform must address both directions simultaneously. Gap: "Diagnosis alone" as the prohibitive criterion is clearly inappropriate, but health history must remain a permissible relevant factor in individualized risk assessments, the distinction between "basis" and "relevant factor" must be explicit in implementing regulations to prevent categorical application under a dangerousness label. Loophole: The prohibition on diagnosis-based exclusion could be circumvented by framing exclusion decisions in "dangerousness" language while still applying categorical criteria; implementing guidelines must require that decision records document the specific behavioral risk factors supporting each restriction, not merely state "dangerousness" as a conclusion. Abuse path: Dangerousness assessment authority could be used to disarm political dissenters or members of disfavored groups through selective referral for evaluation; independent oversight and anti-discrimination enforcement are required safeguards.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-gun-rfl">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">GUN</span>
<span class="family-title">RFL: Red Flag / Extreme Risk Protection Orders</span>
<span class="family-count">0/1 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-RFLS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-RFLS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Federal minimum standards for red flag laws</p>
<p class="rule-plain">A red flag law, formally called an Extreme Risk Protection Order, allows courts to temporarily remove guns from people who show clear warning signs of danger to themselves or others. Federal standards must ensure these orders are available everywhere and that affected people have a fair chance to challenge the removal in court.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Establish federal minimum standards for red flag / extreme risk protection orders with due process protections</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Extreme risk protection orders (ERPOs) allow courts to temporarily remove firearms from individuals who present an imminent danger to themselves or others. States with red flag laws have seen significant reductions in firearm suicides. Federal minimum standards should ensure due process, notice, opportunity to be heard, judicial review, and time limits, while ensuring ERPOs are available in every state. The standard for removal must be clear evidence of imminent risk, not mere allegation; temporary removal must be time-limited and subject to prompt judicial review. As of 2024, 21 states and Washington, DC have ERPO laws; the RAND Corporation found consistent evidence that ERPOs reduce firearm suicide rates by 7–11% (Smart & Morral, 2021). ERPOs address a critical gap in other gun safety measures: background checks and mental health screening apply only at acquisition and capture only formally adjudicated individuals, while ERPOs can address newly emergent threats that post-date acquisition. Gap: ERPO effectiveness depends on law enforcement willingness to petition for orders and judicial willingness to grant them; in jurisdictions where law enforcement or courts are philosophically opposed, orders may be sought and granted at rates far below the actual community risk level. Loophole: A subject who learns of a pending ERPO petition may transfer weapons to third parties before an order is served; ex parte temporary orders address imminent risk but raise due process concerns that must be balanced against the emergency purpose. Abuse path: ERPOs could be used as retaliatory tools, an adversary filing a false or exaggerated petition to cause inconvenience and stigma; the standard of evidence for granting orders must require clear and convincing evidence with meaningful procedural protections, not mere preponderance. Unintended consequence: ERPO proceedings can deter people from disclosing suicidal ideation to family members or employers who might petition for an order; crisis intervention training for petitioners and courts is needed to minimize this chilling effect on help-seeking.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-gun-mil">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">GUN</span>
<span class="family-title">MIL: Militia Regulation and Armed Groups</span>
<span class="family-count">0/5 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-MILS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-MILS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Define "well regulated militia" in enforceable law</p>
<p class="rule-plain">The Second Amendment references a 'well regulated militia,' but that phrase has never been clearly defined in law. Congress must establish a legal definition with real, enforceable standards.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Define 'well regulated militia' in enforceable constitutional and statutory terms</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The Second Amendment's reference to "well regulated Militia" has never been given operational legal meaning. Without a statutory definition, the term cannot be enforced, either to protect legitimate community militias or to prohibit armed groups that claim constitutional protection while refusing accountability. A definition must specify what "well regulated" requires: transparency, safety training, state oversight, and accountability. Without this foundation, the other MIL rules lack clear legal anchoring. <em>District of Columbia v. Heller</em> (2008) held the Second Amendment right to be individual and not dependent on militia service, but left open the definition of "well regulated" and the constitutional status of regulations governing organized armed groups. Gap: Defining "well regulated militia" in statute creates a target for challenge by groups that claim militia status while refusing accountability; the definition must be drawn with sufficient specificity to distinguish legitimate regulated community organizations from armed insurgency groups using militia rhetoric. Loophole: A statutory definition can be acknowledged but then applied selectively; enforcement authority must be vested in a body with both the mandate and resources to assess actual compliance, not a body that relies on self-reporting. Abuse path: Federal law enforcement that treats all militia activity as inherently criminal regardless of whether the group meets accountability standards would chill legitimate community emergency preparedness organizations; the definition must create a clear pathway for lawful regulated militia activity alongside the prohibition on non-compliant armed groups.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-MILS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-MILS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Ban private armies and mercenary groups</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Private armed groups operating outside government oversight, sometimes called private militias or mercenaries, must be prohibited. Armed organizations that answer to no public authority are incompatible with democratic governance.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Ban private armies and mercenary groups</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Private armies and mercenary groups, armed formations that operate outside democratic accountability, refuse state oversight, and function as parallel structures of organized violence, represent a direct threat to democratic order. Most states have statutes prohibiting private paramilitary organizations, but enforcement is inconsistent and federal authority is unclear. This rule establishes a federal floor and closes gaps where existing state laws have failed to prevent armed groups from training for anti-government violence while claiming militia status. A 2020 Georgetown Law Institute review found that 28 states have laws that could potentially apply to unauthorized private militia activity, but only a handful actively enforce them. The January 6, 2021 Capitol attack involved paramilitary groups that had operated openly for years without federal legal action. Gap: The First Amendment protects political association and some speech preparatory to coordinated action; the line between prohibited private military organization and protected political association with incidental armed activity requires precise statutory drafting that survives First Amendment challenge. Loophole: Groups could characterize themselves as "private security" or "sporting clubs" to avoid the "private army" designation; the statute must define prohibited private military organizations by function, organized armed capacity for political or anti-government violence, rather than self-designation. Abuse path: Federal enforcement authority over "private armies" could be weaponized against legitimate political organizations that engage in any form of coordinated activity by an administration hostile to opposition movements; the statute must include clear intent requirements and constitutional safeguards against selective enforcement.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-MILS-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-MILS-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Militia transparency and accountability requirements</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Any organization calling itself a militia must operate transparently, registering members, disclosing its leadership, keeping audited finances, and carrying liability insurance. These requirements bring militias under basic public accountability.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Require militias to maintain membership records, financial transparency, audits, insurance, and disclosed chain of command</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The line between a regulated community defense organization and an unaccountable armed group is accountability. Militias that wish to claim constitutional protection must demonstrate they are "well regulated" by maintaining public membership records, disclosing leadership and chain of command, carrying liability insurance, submitting to regular audits, and meeting safety training standards. These requirements parallel those placed on other organized bodies exercising constitutional rights, political parties, nonprofits, religious organizations, and are not extraordinary burdens. Gap: Compliance with accountability requirements must be verified by an independent authority rather than self-reported; a group that files nominal compliance documents while maintaining operational secrecy satisfies the letter while defeating the purpose; regular third-party audit requirements address this. Loophole: Small informal armed groups could restructure as multiple small "clubs" below any threshold that triggers accountability requirements; the statute’s coverage thresholds must be set to capture all groups that function as organized armed formations regardless of formal organizational size or structure. Abuse path: An administration hostile to citizen militia activity generally could use compliance audits as a pretext for surveillance of political organizations with arms; audit authority must be explicitly limited in scope to accountability compliance, not political ideology or First Amendment-protected speech and association.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-MILS-0004">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-MILS-0004</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Government oversight of militia training</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Governments must be able to review what private militias teach and require in their training. This oversight prevents extremist groups from operating under the cover of a militia designation.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Federal and state governments must have oversight authority over militia training materials and requirements</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Without oversight of training content, militias can train for insurrection while claiming lawful status. Federal and state oversight authority enables review of training curricula, equipment, and operational procedures to ensure compliance with lawful militia standards. This does not prohibit militia training, it ensures that training prepares members for lawful activities (disaster relief, search and rescue, community emergency response) rather than anti-government violence. Oversight is the mechanism that distinguishes a "well regulated" militia from an armed insurgency. Gap: Oversight of "training materials" must be defined precisely to avoid capturing ideological materials (political pamphlets, constitutional commentary) that are unquestionably First Amendment-protected while reaching operational materials (tactical planning against government facilities, deployment procedures for anti-government operations). Loophole: A group could maintain separate training and political education tracks, presenting the former for review while conducting the latter in private; oversight authority must include the ability to assess training in operational context, not merely approve curricula in isolation. Abuse path: Oversight authority could be used to systematically disfavor certain political viewpoints by requiring modification of training materials that include disfavored political content alongside operational training; the oversight mandate must be explicitly limited to operational compliance with lawful militia standards, not ideological content screening. [VERIFY: Constitutional precedents on government oversight of training organizations and First Amendment limits, specifically whether the distinction between ideological content and operational training is judicially recognized.]</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-MILS-0005">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-MILS-0005</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Regulated militias integrated into disaster relief</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Properly vetted and regulated militias should be able to work alongside emergency responders in disasters like floods or wildfires. Channeling these groups into legitimate public-service roles reduces the risk of unaccountable armed groups acting on their own.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Provide mechanisms for regulated militias to train for disaster relief and search and rescue alongside first responders</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Regulated militias can serve legitimate public purposes, particularly in under-resourced areas where disaster response capacity is limited. This rule creates a constructive channel: militias that meet accountability standards can be integrated into emergency management frameworks, training and operating alongside FEMA, the National Guard, fire departments, and local law enforcement. This transforms accountability compliance from a restriction into an opportunity for genuine public service, and establishes the model that distinguishes legitimate regulated militias from prohibited armed groups. FEMA auxiliary and National Guard augmentation frameworks provide existing models for integrating non-standard entities into emergency response structures. Gap: Integration requires background checks, training standards, and command integration protocols that some militia members may refuse; the program must have meaningful vetting requirements rather than treating “registered militia” status as sufficient qualification for public-safety integration. Loophole: Militia groups that achieve FEMA auxiliary status could use that status to claim broader legitimacy while continuing non-compliant activities in other contexts; the program must include ongoing compliance monitoring rather than one-time registration vetting. Unintended consequence: Government-endorsed militia roles could increase the perceived legitimacy and recruitment appeal of militia organizations generally, including groups that do not meet compliance standards; the program must maintain clear public distinction between certified integrated units and all other militia activity.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-gun-lic">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">GUN</span>
<span class="family-title">LIC: Licensing and Waiting Periods</span>
<span class="family-count">0/4 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-LICS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-LICS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Firearm purchaser licensing, permit required before purchase</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Before buying any firearm, a person must obtain a license, completing a background check and safety training first, just like getting a driver's license before getting behind the wheel.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">No person may purchase or acquire a firearm without first obtaining a state-issued firearm purchaser license, valid for five years, requiring completion of safety training, passage of a background check, and a 14-day processing period; the license system applies to all acquisition methods including private sales.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Purchaser licensing is distinct from and stronger than point-of-sale background checks. A background check at the time of purchase can be completed in minutes and provides no time for investigation of recent threats; a purchaser license requires an application process, identity verification, completion of training requirements, and a minimum waiting period before the license is issued. Research on Connecticut's 1995 purchaser licensing law found a 40% reduction in firearm homicides and a 15% reduction in firearm suicides in the years following enactment, compared to counterfactual trends;<sup><a href="#fn4" id="ref4">[4]</a></sup> a 2020 study in <em>Annals of Internal Medicine</em> confirmed the association between permitting laws and reduced firearm mortality. The analogy to motor vehicle licensing is direct: operating a car requires a license demonstrating minimum competence and satisfying legal prerequisites; there is no principled reason firearm acquisition should require less.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-LICS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-LICS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Mandatory waiting period for all firearm purchases</p>
<p class="rule-plain">After buying a gun, there must be a waiting period before taking possession of it. Waiting periods give background checks time to complete and reduce impulsive acts of violence, including suicide.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">A mandatory minimum waiting period of 14 days must apply between the initiation of a firearm purchase transaction and delivery of the firearm; no purchaser license or background check clearance may waive the waiting period.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Waiting periods reduce impulsive firearm violence, particularly suicide and crimes of passion committed in moments of acute emotional distress. Research published in the <em>Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences</em> found that waiting periods reduce gun homicides by roughly 17%.<sup><a href="#fn5" id="ref5">[5]</a></sup> The effect is particularly strong for suicides: firearms are lethal in over 85% of suicide attempts, compared to approximately 5% for other common methods; a waiting period provides an interval during which suicidal crises may resolve or intervention may occur. Current federal law does not require a waiting period, the Brady Act's three-day limit refers only to how long the government may delay a transaction before default-proceeding, not to a minimum delay for safety purposes. A non-waivable 14-day federal minimum ensures the cooling-off function is achieved regardless of whether a background check completes earlier. Research in the <em>Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences</em> found that waiting periods reduce gun homicides by approximately 17% and have especially strong effects on suicide reduction (Luca et al., 2017).<sup><a href="#fn5" id="ref5b">[5]</a></sup> Gap: The 14-day period must be measured from formal purchase initiation, not from the point of background check clearance; dealers must not be permitted to delay submission until a check clears and then restart the 14-day clock. Loophole: An existing license-holder who already owns multiple firearms and wants to purchase one more in a moment of acute emotional distress benefits from no reduction in the waiting period, the cooling-off rationale is most powerful precisely for crisis purchases; the waiting period applies uniformly regardless of prior ownership history. <em>Bruen</em> note: Waiting periods have substantial historical support, the founding era had no same-day purchase culture for firearms, and muskets and long arms required advance ordering; there are sufficient historical analogues to support constitutional viability under the <em>Bruen</em> standard.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-LICS-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-LICS-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Congress must establish a federal firearms purchaser licensing system requiring safety training, a background check, and five-year renewal as a prerequisite for all firearm acquisitions</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Federal law must create a national license for gun buyers that requires safety training, a background check, and renewal every five years. This ensures gun owners remain eligible and knowledgeable throughout their ownership.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Congress must establish a federal firearms purchaser license as a prerequisite for all firearm acquisitions by any method -- purchase, gift, inheritance, or private transfer. The licensing system must require: (a) completion of a state-certified safety course covering safe storage, safe handling, de-escalation techniques, and legal obligations before any license is issued; (b) passage of a written knowledge test demonstrating understanding of firearm law, safe storage requirements, and prohibited-person rules; (c) a background check during the application process with a minimum 14-day processing period -- the license serves as background check clearance, eliminating the need for a separate point-of-sale check; (d) renewal every five years with a current background check at each renewal; (e) mandatory liability insurance for any licensee who owns more than five firearms or any assault-style weapon. The licensing requirement applies to all acquisitions, not solely licensed dealer sales -- closing the private-transfer gap.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: Brady Handgun Violence Prevention Act, 18 U.S.C. § 922(t) (existing point-of-sale background check system supplemented by purchaser licensing); Gun Control Act of 1968, 18 U.S.C. §§ 921-931 (licensing framework for dealers but not purchasers -- this rule creates the missing purchaser-side credential); New York State Rifle &amp; Pistol Association, Inc. v. Bruen, 597 U.S. 1 (2022) -- colonial-era firearm regulation included registration, licensing, and proficiency requirements for militia membership, providing historical tradition support for this rule. Empirical evidence: Crifasi, Doucette, Webster, &amp; Wintemute (2020), Journal of Urban Health, found permit-to-purchase laws significantly associated with lower firearm homicide rates in urban counties; Webster et al. (2014) found Connecticut's 1995 permit-to-purchase law correlated with a 40% reduction in firearm homicides and a 15% reduction in firearm suicides; Missouri's 2007 repeal of its analogous law was followed by a significant increase in firearm homicide rates (Kagawa et al., 2018); the United States is one of the only high-income democracies without a purchaser licensing requirement. Enforcement mechanisms: License as prerequisite for all acquisitions -- closes private-transfer gap; 14-day minimum processing period -- prevents default-proceed on incomplete background checks; five-year renewal with background check -- captures disqualifying events between acquisitions; mandatory liability insurance for concentrated ownership -- private market risk-rating mechanism. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (federal licensing creates a uniform national floor); KERN-0009 (licensing reduces firearm access for prohibited persons through a credential mechanism harder to evade than point-of-sale checks); ENFA-0001 (license-as-prerequisite rather than check-at-sale is a structural enforcement improvement). Adversarial review: Gap -- the license obtained before a disqualifying event occurs remains valid until renewal, meaning an individual who becomes prohibited retains their license for up to five years; an interim revocation mechanism triggered by disqualifying events without waiting for renewal is needed. Loophole -- mandatory liability insurance is only required for owners of more than five firearms or assault-style weapons; the insurance threshold should be set at the first firearm or replaced with a comprehensive insurance requirement for all licensed owners. Unintended consequence -- licensing fees, course costs, and insurance requirements may create a disparate burden on low-income households; a fee waiver or subsidy for households below 200% of the federal poverty line is needed to prevent the system from becoming a wealth-based restriction on lawful firearm ownership. Abuse path -- a hostile state government could refuse to certify any safety courses, effectively nullifying the federal licensing requirement; the statute must include a federal fallback -- if a state fails to certify courses within 12 months of enactment, the federal government must directly offer online-eligible safety training nationwide.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-LICS-0004">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-LICS-0004</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">A federal minimum 10-day waiting period must apply to all firearm purchases with no exception for existing owners or license holders</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Every gun purchase must include at least a 10-day wait before the buyer can take the weapon home, no exceptions for people who already own guns or hold licenses. Research shows waiting periods save lives by reducing impulsive violence and suicide.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Congress must establish a federal minimum 10-day waiting period for all firearm purchases -- applicable regardless of whether the purchaser holds a license, has previously completed a background check, is purchasing a second or subsequent firearm, or is a current or former law enforcement officer. No sale or transfer may be completed until 10 full calendar days after the initiation of the background check or license verification. The three-day default-proceed provision in the Brady Act must be repealed and replaced with a requirement that the sale may not proceed until either a clearance is received or 10 days have elapsed with no disqualification returned.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: Brady Handgun Violence Prevention Act, 18 U.S.C. § 922(t) (existing background check framework with three-day default-proceed provision -- this rule eliminates default-proceed and establishes a 10-day minimum delay); current state waiting period laws range from 3 to 14 days in nine states with no federal minimum; the Brady Act's three-day provision currently operates as a maximum delay before default-proceed rather than a minimum safety period. Empirical evidence: Luca, Malhotra, &amp; Poliquin (2017), Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, found handgun waiting period laws reduce gun homicide rates by approximately 17%, with effects concentrated in crimes of passion and domestic violence; firearms are lethal in over 85% of suicide attempts versus approximately 5% for the most common alternative methods; Everytown Research (2021) found the Charleston loophole enabled at least 11 firearm homicides between 2012 and 2016; nine states currently have waiting periods with documented reductions in suicide rates in all nine. Enforcement mechanisms: 10-day minimum delay with no default-proceed -- closes the Charleston loophole as a structural matter; no-exception rule -- prevents evasion by covering the highest-risk population (persons in crisis with prior purchase records); statutory repeal of three-day default-proceed -- eliminates the specific mechanism that enabled the Charleston church shooting. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (federal minimum preempts state variation below the 10-day floor); KERN-0009 (waiting period directly protects public safety by creating a mandatory cooling-off period between impulse and access); THRV-0001 (reduction in suicide rates is a positive health outcome); ENFA-0001 (no-exception rule and no-default-proceed remove the two main evasion pathways in current law). Adversarial review: Gap -- a 10-day waiting period applies at the point of acquisition but does not address individuals who already own a firearm and are in crisis; suicide prevention for existing gun owners requires separate safe storage and temporary surrender mechanisms, not waiting periods. Loophole -- the waiting period applies to purchases and transfers but could be evaded by renting or borrowing a firearm rather than purchasing it; temporary transfers at shooting ranges should be explicitly exempt (they are not acquisitions) while private loans for other purposes should be covered. Unintended consequence -- a 10-day waiting period may create safety risks for individuals who need a firearm for self-defense and face a documented credible threat; a judicial expedited waiver process for documented credible threats is needed. Abuse path -- a hostile administration could use processing backlogs to effectively deny firearm access indefinitely; the statute must specify that after 10 days with neither clearance nor denial, the purchaser may compel a determination through mandamus in federal court.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-gun-amo">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">GUN</span>
<span class="family-title">AMO: Ammunition Regulation</span>
<span class="family-count">0/2 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-AMOS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-AMOS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Background checks required for all ammunition purchases</p>
<p class="rule-plain">A background check should be required before buying ammunition, not just firearms. This prevents people already barred from owning guns from simply buying the bullets instead.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Background checks equivalent to those required for firearm purchases must be conducted before the sale or transfer of centerfire rifle and pistol ammunition by any licensed or unlicensed seller; prohibited persons may not purchase ammunition in the same circumstances they may not purchase firearms.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Federal law requires background checks for firearm purchases from licensed dealers but imposes no equivalent requirement for ammunition. A person prohibited from purchasing a firearm faces no federal barrier to purchasing unlimited quantities of ammunition. California's ammunition background check law, enacted 2019, provides a functioning model: licensed ammunition vendors must conduct background checks before each sale, with a one-time "basic check" fee and an expedited system for existing registered gun owners. The logical gap is obvious: the same prohibited-person disqualification that applies to the weapon should apply to the ammunition. Without ammunition regulation, firearm safety measures are incomplete, prohibited persons can acquire weapons through illegal channels and arm them through legal ones. California’s 2019 ammunition background check law provides the working model; early implementation data showed that approximately 16% of initial ammunition purchase denials were due to prohibited-purchaser status, confirming that the population of prohibited persons actively seeks to acquire ammunition. Gap: The background check requirement as written covers centerfire rifle and pistol ammunition, it should also extend to shotgun shells and other ammunition categories used in criminal violence to prevent gap-switching to legal ammunition categories. Loophole: Bulk purchases made before the effective date of the law, or by individuals who restock in large quantities before each purchase limitation period, avoid the per-transaction check; the quantity-based reporting threshold in GUNS-AMOS-0002 serves as a complementary mechanism. <em>Bruen</em> note: Ammunition regulation has direct founding-era analogues in gunpowder storage and transport regulations, which controlled the essential component of firearms function; these historical analogues support constitutional viability.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-AMOS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-AMOS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Ammunition sales records and reporting for bulk purchases</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Sellers must keep records of ammunition sales and report unusually large purchases to law enforcement. Bulk ammo stockpiles can be an early warning sign of planned violence.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Licensed firearms dealers and unlicensed bulk sellers must maintain records of ammunition sales exceeding a defined threshold (500 rounds or more in a single transaction) and report bulk purchases to the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives for review.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Mass shooters and domestic terrorists have repeatedly purchased extremely large quantities of ammunition, sometimes tens of thousands of rounds, in the months or weeks preceding attacks, without triggering any law enforcement attention. Bulk ammunition purchase reporting provides a potential early-warning signal and allows ATF to assess whether unusual acquisition patterns indicate planned violence. The reporting threshold must be set at a level that captures genuinely anomalous purchases without sweeping in ordinary lawful activity by hunters and competitive shooters. Records must be maintained with standard privacy protections and subject to the same retention and oversight requirements as other ATF records. The reporting requirement does not prohibit the purchase; it creates a documented record that law enforcement can consult if the individual later becomes the subject of a threat investigation. Mass shooters and domestic terrorists have repeatedly purchased tens of thousands of rounds of ammunition before attacks without triggering law enforcement inquiry; the 2012 Aurora theater shooter purchased approximately 6,000 rounds online in the months preceding the attack. Gap: The 500-round reporting threshold must be calibrated carefully, set low enough to capture anomalous purchases while not sweeping in ordinary activity by hunters during deer season or competitive shooters preparing for major events; ATF must develop context-sensitive review guidelines rather than triggering automatic investigation for every threshold-meeting purchase. Loophole: Purchasers aware of the threshold could split large purchases into multiple sub-threshold transactions across multiple vendors; the reporting rule should aggregate purchases by the same identified buyer within a rolling 30-day window. Abuse path: Bulk purchase reporting data could be used for generalized surveillance of lawful gun owners rather than targeted review of anomalous patterns; the statute must limit permissible data uses to threat assessment and prohibited-purchaser follow-up, with civil cause of action for impermissible use.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-gun-stw">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">GUN</span>
<span class="family-title">STW: Straw Purchase, Trafficking, and Manufacturer Liability</span>
<span class="family-count">0/5 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-STWS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-STWS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Enhanced straw purchase penalties with mandatory minimum prosecution</p>
<p class="rule-plain">A 'straw purchase' is when someone who can legally buy a gun buys it for someone who cannot. Penalties must be stronger and prosecutors must pursue these cases, since straw purchases are a major pipeline for illegal firearms.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Straw purchases of firearms, purchasing a gun on behalf of a prohibited person or any person who has not undergone required background checks, must be prosecuted as a federal felony with mandatory minimum sentencing, and dealers who fail to detect or report obvious straw purchase indicators must face license revocation and civil liability.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Straw purchases: where a legal buyer purchases a firearm on behalf of someone who cannot pass a background check, account for up to 50% of firearm trafficking investigations by ATF and are the most common channel through which prohibited persons obtain firearms.<sup><a href="#fn3" id="ref3">[3]</a></sup> Federal law prohibits straw purchases under 18 U.S.C. § 922(a)(6), but enforcement is inconsistent and penalties are relatively modest. The Bipartisan Safer Communities Act (2022) strengthened trafficking and straw purchase provisions, but implementation gaps remain. Enhanced mandatory prosecution and dealer accountability, requiring dealers to exercise reasonable diligence in detecting straw purchase indicators and imposing license revocation for repeated failures, closes the gap between formal prohibition and functional enforcement. Straw purchases account for a significant share of firearms trafficking investigations, and ATF has documented systematic straw purchase patterns at specific licensed dealers, dealers whose repeated sales to prohibited-person proxies go unaddressed under current enforcement.<sup><a href="#fn3" id="ref3b">[3]</a></sup> Gap: Dealer accountability requires ATF to identify patterns and initiate license revocation proceedings, a regulatory process that can take years and frequently results in no action; the civil liability provision for dealers with obvious straw purchase indicators provides a faster accountability mechanism through the courts. Loophole: "Obvious indicators" of straw purchase must be defined in implementing regulations with specific examples, without clear standards, dealers can claim subjective good-faith ignorance for transactions that are objectively suspicious under any reasonable interpretation. Abuse path: Enhanced mandatory prosecution provisions, if applied selectively by a politically hostile DOJ, could be used to target licensed dealers in politically disfavored regions while enforcement is declined elsewhere; mandatory prosecution standards must include anti-selectivity provisions and Inspector General oversight.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-STWS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-STWS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Firearms trafficking as a standalone federal felony with enhanced penalties</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Buying guns in bulk to resell them illegally, called firearms trafficking, must be its own federal crime with serious penalties. No single law currently covers the full scope of this activity, which fuels violent crime across the country.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Firearms trafficking: the acquisition of multiple firearms for resale outside licensed dealer channels, must be a standalone federal felony with enhanced penalties, distinct from individual straw purchase charges and applicable regardless of whether the ultimate recipient is a prohibited person.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Prior to the Bipartisan Safer Communities Act (2022), there was no standalone federal statute criminalizing firearms trafficking, trafficking charges were assembled from predicate offenses. The 2022 Act created a trafficking offense but with modest maximum penalties. A standalone felony with enhanced sentencing, commensurate with the severity of crimes committed with trafficked weapons, establishes firearms trafficking as a serious federal criminal category, improves prosecution outcomes by simplifying charging decisions, and creates appropriate deterrence for the commercial gun trafficking networks that supply crime guns in cities with strict local regulations. The standalone statute complements, rather than replaces, predicate offense charges and allows prosecutors to pursue trafficking networks at both the distribution and acquisition ends. Prior to the Bipartisan Safer Communities Act (2022), prosecutors assembled trafficking charges from individual predicate offenses; the 2022 Act created trafficking offenses with maximum penalties of 15 years (for trafficking 25+ firearms) and 10 years (for 2–24 firearms), enhanced penalties for volume trafficking and organization-level coordination are needed. Gap: Standalone trafficking statutes are most effective when complemented by robust ATF tracing infrastructure that can link crime guns back to distribution networks rather than only tracking individual transactions. Loophole: Trafficking networks can distribute purchases across multiple straw buyers and multiple dealers to avoid volume thresholds that trigger enhanced penalties; the statute must include conspiracy-to-traffic as a separate offense applicable to coordinators who manage distributed straw-purchase networks. Unintended consequence: Trafficking prosecution resources concentrated on major distribution networks may inadvertently deprioritize individual straw purchases that collectively supply significant crime gun volume.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-STWS-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-STWS-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Firearm manufacturer civil liability for negligent distribution and foreseeable mass violence</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Gun manufacturers must be legally responsible when their distribution choices, like supplying dealers known to funnel guns to the illegal market, lead to foreseeable violence. Victims of this negligence must be able to sue for damages.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The Protection of Lawful Commerce in Arms Act (PLCAA) must be amended to allow civil suits against firearm manufacturers and distributors for negligent distribution practices that foreseeably channel weapons to prohibited persons or to mass-violence perpetrators through known trafficking networks, and for marketing practices that foreseeably encourage unlawful use.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The Protection of Lawful Commerce in Arms Act (2005) broadly immunizes firearm manufacturers from civil liability for crimes committed with their products. While manufacturers should not be liable for the independent criminal acts of third parties using legally sold products, the immunity extends to cases of negligent distribution, knowingly supplying dealers with documented histories of trafficking to prohibited buyers, or maintaining distribution practices that foreseeably channel weapons to high-crime markets. Courts have allowed narrow exceptions (the Sandy Hook families' suit against Remington succeeded on negligent marketing grounds); amending PLCAA to codify and clarify those exceptions restores normal tort accountability principles without eliminating all immunity. A firearm manufacturer that knows its distribution network is supplying gun traffickers and takes no action should bear civil responsibility for foreseeable consequences. The Sandy Hook families’ settlement with Remington’s insurer ($73 million, 2022) demonstrates the mechanism: the narrow negligent marketing exception to PLCAA immunity produced documentary disclosure showing how Remington marketed the AR-15 to young men using military combat imagery. The mechanism works when the immunity is pierced. Gap: Negligent distribution claims require proof that the manufacturer knew or should have known that specific dealers were channeling weapons to prohibited buyers; the evidentiary standard must be calibrated to allow cases with demonstrated knowledge without imposing strict liability on all distribution channels. Loophole: A manufacturer could argue it relied on licensed dealer compliance with federal requirements and had no independent obligation to investigate downstream distribution patterns; the standard should require reasonable monitoring of dealers with documented ATF trace patterns that indicate trafficking. Abuse path: Manufacturer liability claims could be used as litigation harassment by organized plaintiffs’ groups against manufacturers with no demonstrable negligence; judicial management of frivolous claims through existing Federal Rule mechanisms provides the appropriate safeguard, and PLCAA should retain immunity for manufacturers who meet the reasonable distribution monitoring standard.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-STWS-0004">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-STWS-0004</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">The Protection of Lawful Commerce in Arms Act must be repealed or substantially amended to restore civil tort accountability for gun manufacturer negligent design and negligent distribution</p>
<p class="rule-plain">A federal law passed in 2005 gives gun manufacturers near-total immunity from lawsuits, even when their design or distribution choices put people at risk. That special protection must be repealed so the industry faces the same legal accountability as any other manufacturer.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Congress must repeal the Protection of Lawful Commerce in Arms Act (PLCAA) in its entirety, or at minimum amend it to: (a) allow negligent design claims where a firearm lacks safety features reasonable in light of industry standards; (b) allow negligent distribution claims where a manufacturer or distributor knowingly sold to dealers with documented patterns of trafficking-related trace requests or regulatory violations; (c) allow public nuisance claims by states and municipalities for the public health and public safety costs imposed by foreseeable negligent distribution; (d) allow negligence claims where the manufacturer's marketing practices foreseeably attracted purchasers intending unlawful violence, including marketing targeting audiences with documented overlap with anti-government extremism or militia movements.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: Protection of Lawful Commerce in Arms Act, 15 U.S.C. §§ 7901-7903 (2005) -- the statute at issue; Soto v. Bushmaster Firearms International LLC (Conn. 2019) (finding PLCAA's predicate exception permits negligent entrustment and marketing claims); Chiapperini v. Gander Mountain Co. (N.Y. 2014) (negligent distribution under PLCAA predicate exception); Remington Arms Company LLC v. Soto (Conn. 2022) ($73 million settlement in Sandy Hook families' case, producing documentary disclosure of deliberate combat marketing to civilians). No analogous blanket immunity from negligent design or distribution exists in pharmaceuticals, automotive, chemical, or consumer electronics industries under federal law. Empirical evidence: The $73 million Remington settlement produced internal documents showing deliberate marketing of AR-style rifles to civilians using military combat imagery, including materials targeted at audiences with anti-government ideology; ATF trace data showing manufacturers continued supplying dealers with documented trafficking patterns demonstrates the market discipline function that civil liability is intended to perform; approximately 45,000 Americans die from firearms annually (CDC, 2023). Enforcement mechanisms: Repeal of PLCAA -- restores standard products liability, negligent distribution, and public nuisance frameworks across all jurisdictions; predicate exception amendment (if full repeal fails) -- allows claims in the four specified categories through existing tort law without requiring a new federal cause of action. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (federal floor -- no state may provide broader civil immunity for firearm manufacturers than federal law); KERN-0009 (civil liability disciplines product design and distribution decisions in every other industry -- there is no principled basis for the exemption); ENFA-0001 (civil litigation is a structural enforcement mechanism where regulatory enforcement alone is insufficient). Adversarial review: Gap -- PLCAA repeal restores common law tort liability but does not create a federal cause of action; in states with defendant-friendly tort law, recovery may still be difficult; a federal minimum negligence standard for firearm manufacturers may be needed as a backstop. Loophole -- the "predicate exception" approach (amending rather than repealing) leaves the basic immunity structure intact; manufacturers will litigate each of the four categories, creating years of litigation over the scope of the amendment rather than proceeding directly to the merits; full repeal is structurally cleaner. Unintended consequence -- full repeal could produce a wave of litigation including meritless claims against dealers who conducted all required checks and had no knowledge of the buyer's intent; a fee-shifting mechanism against frivolous claims is needed. Abuse path -- a hostile administration could decline to file public nuisance claims authorized by the amended statute; the statute must explicitly authorize states and municipalities to bring their own actions without federal participation.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-STWS-0005">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-STWS-0005</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Universal background check requirements must cover all firearm transfers, the Charleston loophole must be eliminated, and all dealers must maintain electronic records accessible to law enforcement within 24 hours</p>
<p class="rule-plain">A gap in federal law, known as the Charleston loophole, allowed the 2015 church shooter to buy a gun because his background check wasn't completed in three business days. That loophole must be closed: no sale proceeds until the check is done, all private transfers must be checked, and dealers must maintain electronic records accessible to law enforcement within 24 hours.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Congress must: (a) require background checks for all firearm transfers without exception -- private sales, gifts, trades, gun show transfers, and online platform transactions; (b) eliminate the three-day default-proceed provision and replace it with a 10-day hold before any default proceed is permitted; (c) require all federally licensed dealers to maintain electronic point-of-sale records accessible to ATF for trace requests within 24 hours without a judicial warrant; (d) require all states, territories, and federal agencies to submit all disqualifying records -- felony convictions, domestic violence findings, adjudications of mental incompetence, and court-issued protective orders -- to NICS within 48 hours of the event creating the disqualification.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: Brady Handgun Violence Prevention Act, 18 U.S.C. § 922(t) (requires background checks for FFL sales but not private transfers -- this rule closes the private-transfer gap); 18 U.S.C. § 922(t)(1)(B)(ii) (three-day default-proceed provision -- the Charleston loophole -- is expressly repealed); Gun Control Act of 1968, 18 U.S.C. § 923 (FFL recordkeeping authority -- this rule extends and modernizes); U.S. Government Accountability Office, GAO-19-553 (2019) (documented that private-sale gap enables firearms to reach prohibited persons). Empirical evidence: Everytown Research found the Charleston loophole enabled at least 11 firearm homicides between 2012 and 2016, with the 2015 Emanuel AME Church shooting being the most prominent; Dylann Roof's prior drug arrest should have disqualified him but the record was not retrieved within three days; GAO (2019) found that private-sale exemptions remain the primary mechanism by which prohibited persons circumvent federal background check requirements; 48-hour NICS reporting by all states would have caught Roof's disqualifying record before the three-day default window expired. Enforcement mechanisms: Universal transfer coverage -- no exemption for any private transaction; 10-day hold -- eliminates default-proceed as a safety gap; 24-hour electronic record access -- closes the trace delay that enables trafficking networks to stay ahead of law enforcement; 48-hour NICS submission -- addresses the record completeness problem, not just coverage. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (federal minimum requiring all transfers be checked); KERN-0009 (universal background checks directly prevent prohibited persons from accessing firearms); ENFA-0001 (electronic records and 48-hour submission requirements are structural enforcement improvements). Adversarial review: Gap -- universal background checks depend on NICS record completeness; even with 48-hour submission requirements, enforcement against states that fail to submit is currently limited to moral suasion; financial penalties for non-compliant states are needed. Loophole -- private transfers at gun shows can be conducted in a parking lot outside the show, technically avoiding gun show regulations; the statute must cover transfers "facilitated at or in connection with" a gun show or online platform, not only transfers on the premises. Unintended consequence -- requiring background checks on gifts and inheritances within families creates administrative friction for family transfers that have very low trafficking risk; an expedited family transfer protocol with a 24-hour instead of 10-day hold may be appropriate for first-degree family members. Abuse path -- a hostile administration could defund or understaff NICS to create processing backlogs that effectively deny all firearm acquisitions; the 10-day hold must be paired with a mandamus right to compel a determination and a default-approval if the 10 days expire with neither clearance nor denial returned.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-gun-saf">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">GUN</span>
<span class="family-title">SAF: Traceability, Technology, and Safety Measures</span>
<span class="family-count">0/3 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-SAFS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-SAFS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Prohibit manufacture, transfer, or possession of unserialized firearms (ghost guns)</p>
<p class="rule-plain">'Ghost guns' are firearms with no serial number, often assembled at home from kits, that are untraceable by law enforcement. Manufacturing, selling, or possessing these weapons must be illegal.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">No person may manufacture, transfer, or possess a firearm, including frames, receivers, and 3D-printed components, that does not bear a serial number traceable to a licensed manufacturer; all existing unserialized firearms must be serialized by a licensed gunsmith or surrendered within 12 months of enactment.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Ghost guns: unserialized firearms manufactured from parts kits or 3D-printed components, are specifically designed to evade background check requirements and law enforcement tracing systems. The ATF reported that ghost guns recovered at crime scenes increased by over 1,000% between 2016 and 2021.<sup><a href="#fn6" id="ref6">[6]</a></sup> The Biden administration's 2022 ATF rule (Final Rule 2021R-05F) closed some regulatory gaps by requiring manufacturers and dealers to serialize previously exempt kits and frames, but the rule faced legal challenges and enforcement remains uneven. Statutory serialization requirements eliminate the workaround: every functional firearm, regardless of how it was manufactured, must be traceable to a licensed manufacturer and subject to the same background check system that governs licensed dealer sales. Without universal traceability, background check systems, prohibited-person rules, and criminal investigation tools are all undermined at the level of enforcement. Cross-reference: GUN-ACQ-001 through GUN-ACQ-003 (background check requirements that depend on serialization to be effective). ATF reported that ghost guns recovered at crime scenes increased by over 1,000% between 2016 and 2021, from approximately 1,600 to approximately 19,000 annual recoveries.<sup><a href="#fn6" id="ref6b">[6]</a></sup> The Biden administration’s 2022 ATF rule (Final Rule 2021R-05F) required serialization of previously exempt frames and receivers but faced legal challenges; statutory codification eliminates this regulatory vulnerability. Gap: The rule covers physical firearms but must also address 3D-printing files and CNC manufacturing files that enable home production of unserialized weapons; digital distribution of these files through online platforms raises separate First Amendment questions that must be addressed through tailored legislation. Loophole: The 12-month serialization window for existing unserialized firearms depends on owners voluntarily coming forward; there is no practical way to compel serialization without a broader firearms registration framework that this policy area does not currently include; enforcement will necessarily be at the trafficking and crime-recovery stage rather than preventive. <em>Bruen</em> note: Serialization and traceability requirements are among the most constitutionally secure gun regulations, with direct analogues in founding-era proof marks, military inventory requirements, and colonial-era firearms registration laws.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-SAFS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-SAFS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Mandate microstamping technology on all new semi-automatic handguns manufactured for civilian sale</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Microstamping stamps a tiny unique code on bullet casings when a gun fires, letting investigators link shell casings found at a crime scene to a specific weapon. All new civilian semi-automatic handguns must use this technology.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">All new semi-automatic handguns manufactured for civilian sale in the United States must incorporate microstamping technology that imprints a unique identifying code on cartridge cases when fired; implementation must be phased in over five years with no manufacturer exemptions.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Microstamping is a forensic technology that laser-engraves a unique alpha-numeric code on the firing pin and/or breech face of a handgun, so that when the gun fires, the code is stamped on spent cartridge cases. This allows law enforcement to trace a spent cartridge case to the specific firearm that fired it without recovering the weapon itself, a significant advance in solving gun crimes where the weapon is not recovered. California enacted a microstamping law in 2007; implementation has faced delays due to manufacturer resistance and claimed patent limitations. Independent forensic researchers have found microstamping to be technically feasible; objections from gun manufacturers and their trade associations are disputed by peer-reviewed ballistics and forensic science research.<sup><a href="#fn7" id="ref7">[7]</a></sup> Mandatory federal implementation eliminates the problem of manufacturers refusing to adopt the technology voluntarily while retaining market presence. Cross-reference: GUN-SAF-001 (serialization as the ownership traceability complement to microstamping’s fired-case traceability). California enacted a microstamping law in 2007 but implementation was delayed for years due to manufacturer resistance and patent-related claims; independent forensic researchers have confirmed that microstamping is technically feasible, and manufacturer claims of impracticality are disputed by peer-reviewed ballistics literature.<sup><a href="#fn7" id="ref7b">[7]</a></sup> Microstamping directly complements serialization: serialization enables tracing when the weapon is recovered; microstamping enables tracing when only spent casings are recovered at a crime scene. Gap: Microstamping can be partially defeated by replacing the firing pin, a modification that takes minutes and costs little; the statute should require microstamping on the breech face (a harder-to-modify surface) as well, and should require re-stamping on firearms sold secondhand through licensed dealers. Loophole: Weapons manufactured before the effective date are exempt; as the pre-mandate stock cycles through use and crime, the proportion of traceable casings increases slowly over years rather than immediately, the full forensic benefit is realized generationally without a complementary upgrade or buyback program. Unintended consequence: Firearm manufacturers might exit the California market rather than comply (as some have threatened), reducing competition; federal implementation eliminates this market-exit strategy and ensures uniform national forensic benefit.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-SAFS-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-SAFS-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Fund smart gun technology research and remove legal barriers to smart gun market availability</p>
<p class="rule-plain">'Smart guns' are firearms that can only be fired by their authorized user, using a fingerprint or RFID signal, reducing accidents and theft. The government must fund research and remove legal barriers that have kept smart guns off the market.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The federal government must fund research and development of smart gun safety technology including personalization locks, grip recognition, and biometric verification; existing state laws that inadvertently penalize retailers for stocking smart guns must be repealed; smart gun technology may not be mandated as the exclusive option but must be available to consumers choosing it.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Smart guns incorporate electronic or biometric safeguards ensuring only authorized users can fire them. The technology reduces gun theft utility (a stolen smart gun cannot be fired without authorization), child accidental discharge deaths, and suicide access among household members. New Jersey's 2002 Childproof Handgun Law, which mandated smart guns for all future handgun sales once they became available anywhere in the U.S., inadvertently created a market barrier: dealers who stocked smart guns faced threats and boycotts from gun-rights groups opposed to triggering the New Jersey mandate. Federal R&D funding through the National Institute of Justice (NIJ Smart Technology programs) and repeal of mandatory-only state laws allow market development without triggering consumer backlash. Smart gun technology is not mandated for all purchasers; it is developed and made available as a consumer choice for those who prefer it. The market for authorized-user-only firearms is substantial among parents, domestic violence survivors, and households with at-risk members. Cross-reference: GUN-TRN-003 (safe storage, which smart technology complements); GUN-SAF-001 (serialization, traceability and technology as complementary safety frameworks). New Jersey’s 2002 Childproof Handgun Law inadvertently created a market barrier by mandating smart guns for all new handgun sales once any smart gun became commercially available anywhere in the U.S.; this triggered retailer boycotts against any store that stocked smart guns to prevent the New Jersey mandate from activating. The 2019 New Jersey law replaced the mandatory trigger with a more flexible market development requirement. Federal R&D funding and repeal of mandatory-only state laws allow market development without triggering consumer backlash. Gap: Smart gun technology has existed for decades but faces no civilian market penetration; federal R&D funding alone cannot overcome a political boycott, market development incentives (tax credits for smart gun purchases, liability insurance discounts for smart gun owners) may be more effective at building demand than supply-side research investment alone. Loophole: "Available as a consumer choice" does not guarantee stocking by retailers; dealer availability requirements may be necessary to ensure that willing buyers can actually access smart gun products in their local market. Unintended consequence: Mandating smart gun availability may trigger backlash purchasing of non-smart alternatives by politically motivated buyers, temporarily increasing the conventional weapon market; the policy must be accompanied by strong public education about smart gun benefits.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-gun-rsch">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">GUN</span>
<span class="family-title">RSCH: Gun Violence Research</span>
<span class="family-count">0/3 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-RSCH-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-RSCH-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Federal Agencies Must Conduct Ongoing Firearm Injury and Mortality Research</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Federal agencies like the CDC and NIH must fund ongoing research into gun injuries and deaths. For decades, Congress blocked this work; restoring it is essential for understanding what gun safety policies actually work.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Congress must appropriate no less than $50 million annually to the CDC and NIH specifically for firearm injury and mortality research, including suicides, accidents, and homicides; the Dickey Amendment's prohibition on CDC gun research must be repealed by statute. Research must include effectiveness studies on all federal and state gun laws, demographic breakdowns of gun violence, and cost-of-care studies. Research results must be publicly published within 18 months of completion; no appropriations rider may be used to suppress, delay, or defund this research. Knowing suppression, delay, or defunding of required research by any federal official is a federal criminal offense; affected researchers and institutions have a private right of action to compel publication in federal court.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2020 (first congressional appropriation of $25 million for CDC firearm research since 1996); Dickey Amendment, Pub. L. 104-208 (1996) (appropriations rider prohibiting CDC from advocating or promoting gun control -- interpreted by CDC as prohibiting virtually all gun research); Jay Dickey himself recanted the amendment's broad chilling effect before his death in 2017 and called for restoring CDC gun research funding. Empirical evidence: The Dickey Amendment created a roughly 25-year gap in CDC gun violence research; during that period, per-capita firearm mortality research was funded at a fraction of the rate of other comparable public health burdens -- Stark &amp; Shah (2017), JAMA Internal Medicine, found that gun violence research received approximately $1.4 million per death compared to $76.5 million per death for sepsis and $88.7 million per death for cholera; approximately 45,000 Americans die from firearms annually (CDC, 2023); the gap in research means that many gun laws currently in effect have never been rigorously evaluated for effectiveness. Enforcement mechanisms: $50 million minimum appropriation -- exceeds the 2020 appropriation and creates a statutory floor; Dickey Amendment repeal -- removes the research prohibition at the source; 18-month publication requirement -- prevents indefinite delay; mandamus right for researchers -- creates enforcement mechanism against suppression; private right of action -- enables researchers and institutions to compel compliance without federal government assistance. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (federal research mandate creates a uniform national data-generation floor); KERN-0009 (evidence-based policymaking directly supports public safety by ensuring that gun laws are evaluated for effectiveness and corrected when ineffective); ENFA-0001 (criminal offense for knowing suppression is an enforcement mechanism for research integrity). Adversarial review: Gap -- $50 million annually is a statutory floor but not indexed to inflation or to the scale of the public health burden; the floor should be indexed to the annual firearm mortality rate or to NIH budget growth to prevent erosion in real terms. Loophole -- Congress can comply with the floor by shifting existing appropriations from other CDC/NIH programs rather than adding new funding; the appropriation must be additive above a baseline, not substitutable from existing programs. Unintended consequence -- mandatory publication within 18 months may pressure researchers to publish preliminary findings before they are methodologically sound; the publication requirement should specify peer review as a precondition, not just agency sign-off. Abuse path -- a hostile administration could slow-walk research approvals to prevent publication within 18 months; the mandamus right must specify that failure to initiate a required study within 6 months of appropriation is itself a structural violation.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-RSCH-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-RSCH-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Establish a Real-Time National Firearm Injury and Death Surveillance Database</p>
<p class="rule-plain">A national, continuously updated database must track gun injuries and deaths across the country. Accurate, timely data is the foundation of any effective public health response to gun violence.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The CDC must establish and maintain a real-time national firearm injury surveillance system, modeled on the National Electronic Injury Surveillance System, receiving data from all hospital emergency departments, trauma centers, and medical examiners within 72 hours of a firearm-related injury or death. Data must be disaggregated by weapon type, location, circumstance (self-inflicted, assault, law enforcement, accident), demographics, and legal status of the firearm. Annual reports must be publicly published; data must be available to researchers under a qualified researcher access program. Failure by a covered reporting entity to submit required data is a federal civil offense subject to withholding of federal health funding; any researcher or institution denied access under the qualified researcher program has a private right of action to compel disclosure in federal court.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: Public Health Service Act, 42 U.S.C. § 247b (CDC authority to establish disease and injury surveillance systems -- firearm injuries are a public health matter within this authority); the National Electronic Injury Surveillance System (NEISS) is the existing model -- a probability sample of hospital emergency departments that produces national injury estimates but lacks the comprehensiveness, granularity, and real-time reporting required for firearm policy evaluation; the Gun Violence Archive, a non-governmental organization, currently maintains the most comprehensive real-time gun violence database in the United States -- a function that should be a federal government responsibility. Empirical evidence: The United States lacks a comprehensive, real-time, federally maintained database of firearm injuries and deaths; existing data sources (CDC WISQARS, NEISS, FBI NIBRS) are fragmented, delayed by 1-2 years, and do not include granular weapon-type or circumstances data needed for policy evaluation; the Gun Violence Archive demonstrates that real-time tracking is technically feasible; without comprehensive surveillance data, laws cannot be evaluated for effectiveness and public health responses cannot be calibrated. Enforcement mechanisms: 72-hour reporting requirement -- creates a near-real-time data stream rather than annual or multi-year delays; federal health funding withholding for non-compliant entities -- financial enforcement mechanism; private right of action for researchers denied access -- prevents bureaucratic suppression of data access. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (federal surveillance system creates a national data floor that no state can undercut); KERN-0009 (surveillance data is the empirical foundation for evidence-based gun safety policy -- without it, policymakers are acting on incomplete information); ENFA-0001 (funding withholding and private right of action are enforcement mechanisms that do not depend on federal prosecutorial discretion). Adversarial review: Gap -- 72-hour reporting depends on hospital systems having the required EHR infrastructure; rural hospitals and under-resourced trauma centers may lack capacity; a federal grant program for reporting infrastructure upgrades is needed. Loophole -- "legal status of the firearm" data is only available if the firearm is recovered and traced; for unrecovered firearms, the legal status cannot be determined; the database should require reporting of whether a firearm was recovered and, if so, what trace results showed, acknowledging that many entries will be incomplete. Unintended consequence -- creating a federal database linking injury data to firearms type, location, and demographics raises privacy concerns; the qualified researcher access program must include robust de-identification requirements and prohibitions on individual identification. Abuse path -- a hostile administration could classify the research database as law enforcement sensitive, restricting public access; the statute must specify that aggregate public reports and de-identified researcher access are mandatory and not subject to law enforcement classification.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-RSCH-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-RSCH-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">All Federal Gun Laws Must Include Mandatory Five-Year Effectiveness Evaluations</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Every federal gun safety law must be reviewed every five years to measure whether it is actually reducing harm. Laws that aren't working should be strengthened or replaced based on evidence, not politics.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Every federal firearms law and significant federal regulation must include a sunset-with-renewal provision requiring: a five-year effectiveness evaluation by the CDC, NIH, and DOJ; public testimony on findings; and affirmative congressional reauthorization to continue. Evaluation criteria must include: reduction in firearm mortality rates, compliance rates, effects on lawful gun ownership, and equity impacts across demographic groups. Laws that demonstrably increase harm or have no measurable benefit may be suspended pending revision. Congressional failure to timely commission a required evaluation is a structural violation subject to mandamus in federal court on petition by any affected person or organization.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: No existing federal firearms law includes mandatory effectiveness evaluation requirements; this provision applies the general principle of evidence-based sunset provisions established in other regulatory contexts (e.g., the Paperwork Reduction Act's periodic review requirements) to firearms specifically. The Congressional Research Service, CDC, NIH, and DOJ already have legal authority to study federal law effectiveness; this rule makes the evaluation mandatory and ties it to a reauthorization requirement. Empirical evidence: The 1994 Assault Weapons Ban expired in 2004 without any comprehensive federal evaluation of its effectiveness; the Brady Act has never been comprehensively evaluated for its impact on total firearm mortality; most gun laws currently in effect have no rigorous impact evaluation -- without evaluation data, Congress is making reauthorization and revision decisions without an empirical basis; the absence of mandatory evaluation is itself a policy failure that compounds every other gun safety gap. Enforcement mechanisms: Sunset-with-renewal requirement -- if Congress fails to commission the required evaluation, the law may not be extended; mandamus right for any affected person -- any citizen, researcher, or organization can compel the commissioning of a required evaluation through federal court; public testimony on findings -- prevents results from being buried in agency reports. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (the evaluation requirement applies uniformly to all federal firearms laws); KERN-0009 (mandatory evaluation ensures that ineffective laws are identified and corrected, and effective laws are maintained); ENFA-0001 (mandamus for delayed evaluation is an enforcement mechanism for the evaluation requirement itself). Adversarial review: Gap -- "significant federal regulation" is not defined; ATF rule-making must be included in the evaluation requirement, not just statutes, or the most active regulatory layer (ATF rules) escapes review. Loophole -- Congress can technically commission an evaluation and then ignore its findings, meeting the procedural requirement while defeating the substantive purpose; the statute should require that the reauthorization act include a written response to evaluation findings, explaining why the law is being reauthorized despite adverse findings (or why the findings were rejected). Unintended consequence -- requiring affirmative congressional reauthorization every five years creates a recurring opportunity for an anti-gun-safety Congress to let beneficial laws expire through inaction; the default rule if Congress fails to act should be continuation of the law pending evaluation, not expiration. Abuse path -- a hostile administration could manipulate evaluation methodology or suppress findings; all evaluation contracts must be awarded through competitive bidding with independent peer review, and raw data must be made publicly available regardless of findings.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-gun-safe">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">GUN</span>
<span class="family-title">SAFE: Safe Storage</span>
<span class="family-count">0/3 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-SAFE-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-SAFE-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">All Firearms Must Be Stored in Locked Storage When Not Under the Owner's Direct Control</p>
<p class="rule-plain">When a gun is not in a person's hands, it must be stored in a locked container. Secure storage prevents stolen weapons from reaching criminal hands and keeps children from accessing loaded firearms.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Federal law must require that any firearm not in the immediate physical possession of its lawful owner be stored unloaded in a locked container, gun safe, or with a trigger lock installed; storage requirements apply in all residences where a minor under 18 is present or has access. Violation of storage requirements when a minor gains access resulting in injury or death is a federal criminal offense with mandatory minimum penalties. Manufacturers must include a certified gun lock or lockbox with every firearm sold. The ATF must publish minimum standards for certified locks and storage devices. Any person injured by a firearm accessed by a minor due to unlawful storage has a private right of action against the firearm owner for civil damages.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: No federal safe storage law currently exists; 11 states have Child Access Prevention (CAP) laws with varying requirements; Massachusetts has the most comprehensive state safe storage law (Mass. Gen. Laws ch. 140 § 131L), requiring locked storage for all firearms; Kolbe v. Hogan, 849 F.3d 114 (4th Cir. 2017) (en banc) found Maryland's assault weapons law constitutional, supporting the view that storage requirements do not violate the Second Amendment; District of Columbia v. Heller, 554 U.S. 570 (2008) explicitly held that trigger lock requirements for operable firearms in the home may be unconstitutional as applied to a person who needs immediate access for self-defense -- this rule must include a reasonable self-defense access exception for adults who are not in a household with minors. Empirical evidence: Monuteaux et al. (2019), Pediatrics, found that states with CAP laws have significantly lower rates of youth firearm suicide and unintentional firearm deaths; approximately 4.6 million children live in homes with unlocked, loaded firearms (Azrael et al., 2018, Annals of Internal Medicine); unintentional firearm deaths among children under 15 are preventable through storage requirements; storage requirements are associated with 13% reductions in youth firearm suicide rates in states with CAP laws. Enforcement mechanisms: Manufacturer inclusion of certified lock with every firearm sold -- ensures the storage tool is available at time of purchase; ATF minimum standards for certified locks -- prevents compliance with ineffective devices; mandatory minimum criminal penalty for violations when a minor is injured -- creates meaningful deterrence beyond civil liability; private right of action for injured persons -- enforcement independent of prosecutorial discretion. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (federal floor for safe storage requirements -- states may enact stronger requirements); KERN-0009 (safe storage directly prevents youth firearm injuries and deaths); THRV-0001 (preventing childhood firearm deaths is a thriving population outcome); ENFA-0001 (mandatory minimums and private right of action are enforcement mechanisms). Adversarial review: Gap -- Heller's self-defense carve-out means that a storage requirement for a person living alone without minors may be vulnerable to constitutional challenge; the statute needs a self-defense access exception that preserves the storage requirement for households with minors while not overreaching into Heller's protected right to operable home defense. Loophole -- "immediate physical possession" creates a gap: a firearm left in a car in the driveway, not on the owner's person but accessible to a minor, may not meet the residency-based trigger; the statute should cover any location accessible to a minor, not only residences. Unintended consequence -- mandatory minimums for storage violations when a minor is injured may result in prosecutions of grieving parents who have already suffered a traumatic loss; prosecutorial guidelines or an affirmative defense for cooperation with investigation and storage upgrade may reduce the harshness of outcomes in tragic cases. Abuse path -- a hostile administration could decline to promulgate ATF minimum standards for certified locks, creating a compliance gap; the statute must require ATF to publish standards within 12 months of enactment and specify that any commercially available padlock meeting a specified ANSI security grade qualifies as an interim standard pending ATF rulemaking.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Approximately 4.6 million children in the U.S. live in homes with loaded, unlocked guns.<sup><a href="#fn8" id="ref8">[8]</a></sup> An estimated 380,000 firearms are stolen from homes annually.<sup><a href="#fn9" id="ref9">[9]</a></sup></p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-SAFE-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-SAFE-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Federal Child Access Prevention Law, Criminal Liability for Negligent Storage</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Gun owners who negligently leave firearms accessible to children must face criminal liability when that results in harm. These laws hold adults accountable and create a legal incentive to store weapons safely.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">It is a federal criminal offense for any person to negligently store or leave a firearm in a manner that allows access by a minor who then uses the firearm to injure themselves or another person. Negligence is presumed when: no trigger lock is in place; the firearm is loaded; or no locked storage is used. Affirmative defenses include: the firearm was taken by force; or the minor accessed the storage through unauthorized means that were not foreseeable. Prosecution does not require that the minor actually fire the weapon, mere access while the underlying negligent storage occurred constitutes the offense. Any person injured as a result of a minor's access under negligent storage conditions has a private right of action for civil damages against the storing party.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: The federal Child Access Prevention (CAP) concept mirrors state CAP laws in 11 states; the most protective state models (Florida, California, Massachusetts) impose criminal liability when a minor accesses an improperly stored firearm and uses it to injure themselves or another person; Negligence per se is available under state tort law in states with CAP laws -- a federal CAP creates a national floor. No federal CAP law currently exists. The Heller self-defense access exception applies: if a person requires the firearm for immediate self-defense, stored-but-accessible configurations may be defensible; the negligence presumption must be rebuttable in documented self-defense-readiness contexts. Empirical evidence: Monuteaux et al. (2019), Pediatrics, found states with CAP laws had a 13% lower rate of youth firearm suicide; Crifasi et al. (2018), JAMA Pediatrics, found that CAP laws reduce unintentional firearm deaths among children; Everytown (2023) reported over 350 unintentional shootings by children annually in the United States; criminal liability for negligent storage, not just civil liability, is the deterrence mechanism -- civil suits are available only after an injury; criminal liability is prospective. Enforcement mechanisms: Presumption of negligence -- shifts burden of proof to the storing party rather than requiring the prosecution to prove each element; access-without-discharge theory -- captures near-miss events that would otherwise go unprosecuted; private right of action for injured persons -- enforcement independent of local prosecutorial discretion; affirmative defenses -- preserves fairness by excluding cases of theft and unforeseeable access. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (federal criminal floor -- states may enact stronger liability rules); KERN-0009 (criminal CAP law directly protects children from foreseeable firearm harm); THRV-0001 (protecting children from firearm injury is a thriving population outcome); ENFA-0001 (criminal liability rather than civil-only enforcement is a structural improvement in deterrence). Adversarial review: Gap -- the "minor accesses storage" theory requires that access be detected or provable; many near-misses go undetected and therefore unprosecuted; the statute should also include a negligent storage offense that does not require access by a minor -- storing a loaded, unsecured firearm in a household with a minor is itself an offense regardless of whether access occurs. Loophole -- "unauthorized means that were not foreseeable" is an affirmative defense that firearm owners will routinely invoke; a child finding a hidden-but-unlocked firearm does not necessarily involve "unauthorized means" -- the defense should be narrowly drafted to cover only cases of forced entry or lock-defeating tools. Unintended consequence -- the criminal CAP offense may be applied unevenly across demographic groups; mandatory prosecution guidelines rather than prosecutorial discretion would reduce demographic disparities in enforcement. Abuse path -- the access-without-discharge theory could be used to prosecute safe storage in edge cases; the statute must require that the prosecution establish that the storage configuration created a reasonably foreseeable risk of access -- not merely that access occurred from any configuration.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-SAFE-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-SAFE-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Federal Tax Credit for Certified Firearm Storage Equipment</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Gun owners should receive a federal tax credit when they buy certified gun safes or lock boxes. Making safe storage affordable encourages compliance and reduces the number of firearms accessible to children or thieves.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">A refundable federal tax credit of up to $500 per household must be available for the purchase of certified firearm storage equipment (gun safes, lockboxes, quick-access safes certified to ATF standards). The credit is available once per three-year period per household; income phase-out begins at $100,000 AGI. Certified equipment must meet minimum theft-resistance and fire-resistance standards promulgated by the ATF. The ATF must maintain a publicly accessible list of certified equipment manufacturers; fraudulent certification of non-compliant equipment by a manufacturer is a federal criminal offense, and purchasers who relied on a fraudulent certification have a private right of action against the certifying manufacturer for damages.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: 26 U.S.C. § 25C (existing residential energy efficiency tax credit -- the structural model for equipment-linked refundable credits); 26 U.S.C. § 36B (premium tax credit -- the model for income-phase-out structure); the ATF has authority to promulgate certification standards for locking devices under 18 U.S.C. § 922(z) (existing authority for licensed dealer provision of locking devices). No federal firearm storage equipment tax credit currently exists. Empirical evidence: Cost is a documented barrier to safe storage adoption; gun safe prices range from approximately $50 for a basic lockbox to over $1,000 for a full-size safe; a $500 refundable credit makes even higher-end secure storage accessible to low- and middle-income households; Azrael et al. (2018), Annals of Internal Medicine, found that approximately 54% of firearm owners who do not use safe storage cite cost or lack of information as reasons; similar equipment credits (ENERGY STAR appliances, EV chargers) have been shown to drive significant adoption increases within 1-2 years of enactment. Enforcement mechanisms: Refundable credit -- accessible to households with no tax liability, ensuring coverage for the lowest-income firearm owners; three-year renewal period -- creates ongoing incentive for upgrading storage equipment; ATF certification standards -- prevents credit being claimed for ineffective devices; criminal penalty for fraudulent certification -- deters manufacturers from obtaining certification for non-compliant equipment. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (federal credit creates a uniform national incentive -- states may supplement but cannot undercut); KERN-0009 (storage equipment reduces firearm access by minors and in theft situations); ECON-0002 (the credit is a market mechanism that does not compel storage but creates strong financial incentive -- consistent with voluntary compliance approach); THRV-0001 (reducing youth firearm deaths is a thriving population outcome). Adversarial review: Gap -- a $500 credit is insufficient for a high-end gun safe; households with large firearm collections (10+ firearms) need multi-gun safes that cost $1,000-$3,000; the credit cap should be higher or the renewal period shorter for households that report more than five firearms. Loophole -- the credit is available "once per three-year period" but a household could claim the credit, sell the certified equipment, and purchase a new safe every three years; the statute should require that the equipment remain in the household for at least two years or the credit is recaptured. Unintended consequence -- the refundable credit provides a windfall to higher-income households who would have purchased a safe regardless; the income phase-out beginning at $100,000 AGI should be reduced to $75,000 AGI to target the benefit at households where cost is actually a barrier. Abuse path -- a hostile ATF could delay promulgating certification standards indefinitely; the statute must require ATF to publish standards within 12 months and must specify that any ANSI/UL-rated safe at a specified security level qualifies as an interim standard pending rulemaking.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-gun-traf">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">GUN</span>
<span class="family-title">TRAF: Gun Trafficking</span>
<span class="family-count">0/3 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-TRAF-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-TRAF-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Federal Law Limits Handgun Purchases to One Per Person Per Month</p>
<p class="rule-plain">No person may buy more than one handgun per month under federal law. This limit disrupts bulk buying by traffickers who purchase many guns at once to resell illegally on the street.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Federal law must limit the purchase of handguns by a single person to one firearm per 30-day period from any combination of licensed dealers; the ATF must maintain a real-time database enabling dealers to verify whether a purchaser has made a handgun purchase in the prior 30 days. Straw purchasing, buying a firearm on behalf of another person who could not legally purchase it, must carry mandatory minimum sentences of three years with no probation eligible. The ATF must publish annual reports on one-gun-per-month limit violations and straw purchase prosecutions. Any person harmed by a firearm obtained through a straw purchase or in violation of purchase limits has a private right of action against the purchasing party and, where the dealer knew or recklessly disregarded the violation, against the dealer.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: Virginia enacted a one-gun-per-month limit in 1993, then repealed it in 2012, then re-enacted it in 2021 (Va. Code § 18.2-308.2:2) -- Virginia's data provides before/after evidence on trafficking diversion effects; South Carolina had a one-gun-per-month law from 1975 to 2004; federal law currently imposes no purchase frequency limit; 18 U.S.C. § 922(a)(6) prohibits straw purchases but with inconsistent enforcement; Abramski v. United States, 573 U.S. 169 (2014) confirmed that straw purchases violate federal law even when the ultimate buyer is legally eligible to own a firearm. Empirical evidence: Webster, Crifasi, &amp; Vernick (2014), Journal of Urban Health, found Virginia's one-gun-per-month repeal was associated with a 61% increase in Virginia-sourced crime guns recovered in Northeast states; ATF trace data consistently shows that a small number of dealers account for a disproportionate share of crime gun sales, and multiple same-month purchases from these dealers are a key trafficking indicator; mandatory minimum sentencing for straw purchasing addresses a documented enforcement gap where prosecutors often decline to bring straw purchase cases because the penalty is insufficient to justify resource expenditure. Enforcement mechanisms: Real-time ATF database for dealer verification -- closes the information gap that currently makes per-month limit violations undetectable; three-year mandatory minimum for straw purchasing -- creates deterrence sufficient to justify prosecution; annual ATF reporting -- creates public accountability for enforcement activity; private right of action for harmed persons -- enforcement independent of prosecutorial discretion. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (federal purchase limit creates a uniform national floor -- Virginia's experience shows state-level limits can be evaded by purchasing in adjacent states); KERN-0009 (purchase limits directly reduce bulk handgun acquisition for trafficking); ENFA-0001 (real-time database and mandatory minimums are structural enforcement improvements). Adversarial review: Gap -- the one-gun-per-month limit applies only to licensed dealers; private sales, which are already addressed separately, remain outside the verification database unless universal background checks are enacted; this rule is most effective when paired with universal transfer requirements. Loophole -- a purchaser who reaches the monthly limit at licensed dealers can still purchase from private sellers in states without universal background check requirements; the monthly limit must be paired with universal transfer requirements to close this gap. Unintended consequence -- a three-year mandatory minimum for straw purchasing may be disproportionately applied against low-income individuals who purchased firearms for family members without understanding the legal prohibition; a prosecutorial guidance requirement and a first-offense education-in-lieu-of-prosecution pathway for non-commercial straw purchases may be appropriate. Abuse path -- the real-time ATF database creates a de facto handgun purchaser registry; the statute must specify that database records are accessible only for point-of-sale verification and ATF trace requests, not for general law enforcement or immigration purposes.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Virginia's one-handgun-per-month law was repealed in 2012 and reinstated in 2020.<sup><a href="#fn10" id="ref10">[10]</a></sup> Research links the law's repeal to increased gun trafficking to northeastern states.<sup><a href="#fn11" id="ref11">[11]</a></sup></p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-TRAF-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-TRAF-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">All Lost or Stolen Firearms Must Be Reported to Law Enforcement Within 48 Hours</p>
<p class="rule-plain">If your gun is lost or stolen, you must report it to police within 48 hours. Quick reporting helps law enforcement recover weapons before they're used in crimes and helps track how guns move from legal to illegal hands.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Federal law must require any person who discovers that a firearm they own has been lost or stolen to report the loss or theft to local law enforcement and the ATF within 48 hours of discovery. Failure to report is a federal civil offense subject to a $1,000 fine per firearm for a first offense and $5,000 for subsequent offenses; knowing failure to report to conceal trafficking is a federal criminal offense. Licensed dealers must report inventory theft within 24 hours. The ATF must cross-reference the stolen gun database with all crime scene ballistics evidence. Any person harmed by a firearm not reported as stolen or lost in violation of this section has a private right of action against the non-reporting owner for civil damages arising from foreseeable subsequent criminal use.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: Approximately 10 states (including California, Connecticut, Hawaii, Massachusetts, Michigan, New Jersey, New York, Ohio, and Rhode Island) have lost or stolen reporting requirements; no federal requirement exists; ATF's National Tracing Center traces recovered crime guns under 18 U.S.C. § 923(g) but depends on dealer records, not stolen gun reports from owners; the "claimed stolen" defense is frequently raised in prosecutions of illegal gun transfers -- a reporting requirement undermines this defense by establishing that owners either reported the theft or did not. Empirical evidence: Everytown Research estimates approximately 380,000 firearms are stolen annually in the United States; the majority of stolen firearms are recovered in crimes rather than returned to their owners; ATF trace analysis shows that "straw purchase then report stolen" is a documented trafficking method -- the 48-hour reporting requirement combined with criminal liability for knowing non-reporting directly addresses this mechanism; Cook &amp; Ludwig (2003) found that "time-to-crime" (interval between retail sale and recovery at a crime scene) is a key indicator of trafficking, and stolen gun reporting dramatically improves law enforcement's ability to distinguish diverted-at-sale from stolen-post-sale. Enforcement mechanisms: Civil fine per firearm for first offense -- cost-effective enforcement for negligent non-reporting; criminal offense for knowing non-reporting to conceal trafficking -- targets the actual trafficking conduct; 24-hour dealer reporting requirement -- dealers have inventory records that make compliance straightforward; cross-reference with crime scene ballistics -- enables use of stolen gun data in investigations and prosecutions; private right of action -- enforcement independent of civil penalty collection by ATF. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (federal reporting requirement creates a uniform national floor); KERN-0009 (stolen gun reporting directly addresses a documented trafficking mechanism); ENFA-0001 (tiered enforcement -- civil fines for negligence, criminal penalties for knowing concealment -- matches penalty to culpability). Adversarial review: Gap -- "discovers" that a firearm is lost or stolen is an ambiguous trigger; a person may delay reporting by claiming they only recently "discovered" the loss; the statute should require reporting within 48 hours of the earlier of actual or constructive knowledge of the loss or theft. Loophole -- a person who has trafficked a firearm but not yet been discovered can report the firearm as stolen after the crime, attempting to use the stolen report as a defense; the statute must specify that a stolen report filed after law enforcement contact regarding the firearm is not an affirmative defense and is itself evidence of consciousness of guilt. Unintended consequence -- a $1,000 civil fine for a first offense may be disproportionate for a person who suffered a burglary and was traumatized or unaware of the reporting requirement; a grace period of 72 hours with no penalty if the person contacts law enforcement upon discovery may be more appropriate than an immediate fine for the first day of non-reporting. Abuse path -- the stolen gun database could be used to track gun owners who report firearms stolen, creating a de facto registration mechanism; database access must be limited to ATF trace requests and active criminal investigations, with no general law enforcement query permitted.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-TRAF-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-TRAF-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">All Firearms Must Bear Permanent Serial Numbers; Ghost Guns Are Prohibited</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Every legally manufactured or sold firearm must have a permanent serial number that cannot be removed or defaced. Serial numbers let law enforcement trace guns used in crimes, firearms without them make investigations nearly impossible.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Federal law must require that all firearms, including those manufactured at home, printed with 3D printers, or assembled from kits, bear a permanent, machine-readable serial number registered with the ATF at the time of manufacture or completion. The ATF must establish a simplified registration process for home-manufactured firearms, with no transfer allowed until the firearm is registered and serialized. Sale, transfer, or possession of an unserialized firearm is a federal felony carrying a mandatory minimum of two years. The ATF's ghost gun rule must be codified in statute and not subject to reversal by executive action. Any person harmed by an unserialized firearm has a private right of action against any person who sold, transferred, or manufactured the firearm without the required serial number.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: Gun Control Act of 1968, 18 U.S.C. § 922(k) (prohibits possession of firearms with removed or obliterated serial numbers -- this rule extends the logic to require serialization at manufacture); ATF Final Rule 2021R-05F (2022) (required serialization of "privately made firearms" including frames, receivers, and completion kits -- subject to legal challenge); Garland v. VanDerStok, No. 23-852 (Supreme Court, 2024) (Court upheld ATF's authority to regulate ghost gun kits as "firearms" under the Gun Control Act -- statutory codification removes dependence on ATF rulemaking authority that could be reversed). Empirical evidence: ATF reported ghost guns recovered at crime scenes increased from approximately 1,600 in 2016 to approximately 19,344 in 2021, a 1,083% increase; ghost guns are disproportionately recovered in urban areas and in juvenile gun violence cases (ATF Ghost Gun Report, 2022); unserialized firearms cannot be traced to prior owners, making criminal investigation and trafficking interdiction substantially more difficult; the scale of the increase demonstrates that the absence of a serialization requirement for home manufacture creates a significant loophole in the broader background check and tracing framework. Enforcement mechanisms: Mandatory minimum of two years for possession, sale, or transfer of unserialized firearm -- creates meaningful deterrence; statutory codification of ATF ghost gun rule -- closes the regulatory vulnerability that allowed VanDerStok-type challenges to ATF rulemaking authority; ATF simplified registration for home-manufactured firearms -- creates a compliance pathway rather than just a penalty; transfer prohibition until registered -- prevents unserialized home-manufactured firearms from entering commerce. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (federal serialization requirement creates a uniform national floor); KERN-0009 (serialization is the foundation of the firearms tracing system -- without it, background checks, trafficking investigations, and crime gun tracing all lose effectiveness); ENFA-0001 (statutory codification eliminates the regulatory vulnerability; mandatory minimum creates deterrence). Adversarial review: Gap -- the 12-month period for registration of existing unserialized firearms depends on owners voluntarily coming forward; there is no practical mechanism to identify or compel registration from owners who do not wish to register; the mandatory minimum for possession after the deadline serves as the enforcement backstop but may be under-enforced. Loophole -- digital manufacturing files for 3D-printed firearms or CNC-machined components are distributed online; prohibiting the physical firearm without addressing the digital distribution channel leaves the supply mechanism intact; separate legislation addressing digital distribution of undetectable firearm manufacturing files is needed to close this gap. Unintended consequence -- the two-year mandatory minimum for possession of an unserialized firearm may be disproportionate as applied to collectors of antique firearms manufactured before serial numbers were required; an antique firearms exception mirroring the existing GCA antique firearms exemption (pre-1899) should be included. Abuse path -- a hostile ATF could make the simplified registration process so burdensome that it creates a practical barrier to home-manufacture registration; the statute should specify maximum documentation requirements for home-manufactured firearm registration and a 30-day processing deadline.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The ATF estimated 23,906 unserialized ghost guns were recovered at crime scenes between 2016 and 2020,<sup><a href="#fn12" id="ref12">[12]</a></sup> representing a dramatic increase in untraceable firearms. Cross-reference: GUNS-SAFS-0001 (ghost gun prohibition in the SAF family).</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-gun-excl">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">GUN</span>
<span class="family-title">EXCL: Industry Accountability</span>
<span class="family-count">0/2 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-EXCL-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-EXCL-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Repeal Protection of Lawful Commerce in Arms Act Immunity for Negligent Conduct</p>
<p class="rule-plain">A 2005 law gives gun manufacturers broad protection from lawsuits, even when their negligent actions, like knowingly selling to distributors that supply illegal dealers, cause harm. That special immunity must be repealed so victims can hold manufacturers accountable in court.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The Protection of Lawful Commerce in Arms Act (PLCAA) immunity from civil liability for gun manufacturers and dealers must be repealed as applied to: negligent entrustment; knowing or reckless sales to straw purchasers; failure to implement required inventory controls; defective product design; and deceptive marketing to minors or civilians of military-style weapons. Manufacturers and dealers retain protection from liability for unforeseeable criminal acts by purchasers. Any state law providing broader civil immunity than federal law for firearm manufacturers is preempted. Harmed individuals, survivors, and municipalities have a private right of action in federal court for damages arising from the above categories of negligent or reckless conduct; class actions are expressly permitted.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: Protection of Lawful Commerce in Arms Act, 15 U.S.C. §§ 7901-7903 (2005) -- repealed as to the five specified categories; the PLCAA's existing predicate exception (§ 7903(5)(A)(iii)) has been interpreted to permit negligent entrustment and marketing claims in some courts but not others (compare Soto v. Bushmaster (Conn. 2019) permitting claim with Ganim v. Smith &amp; Wesson (Conn. 1999) barring it pre-PLCAA); Abramski v. United States, 573 U.S. 169 (2014) (straw purchase liability confirmed); Remington Arms settlement (2022) ($73 million) following Soto decision demonstrates that civil liability works when the immunity is pierced. Note: this position (GUNS-EXCL-0001) is a targeted amendment addressing specific harmful conduct categories; GUNS-STWS-0004 addresses full PLCAA repeal -- the two positions are not duplicative but rather present a minimum acceptable reform (this position) alongside the preferred policy (STWS-0004). Empirical evidence: The Remington $73 million settlement is the direct evidence that civil liability disciplines manufacturer conduct; internal Remington documents disclosed in that litigation showed deliberate marketing to at-risk audiences; ATF trace data shows that approximately 5% of FFL dealers account for approximately 90% of crime gun sales -- negligent distribution liability targets this concentration; the PLCAA immunity creates a market subsidy by removing civil liability costs that would otherwise discipline product design and distribution decisions. Enforcement mechanisms: Targeted repeal as to five categories -- preserves manufacturer protection for unforeseeable third-party criminal acts while removing immunity for manufacturer negligence; federal preemption of broader state immunity -- prevents states from providing immunity Congress has revoked; class action authorization -- enables aggregation of claims that would be individually uneconomic; private right of action in federal court -- creates a venue that does not depend on state court treatment. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (federal preemption of broader state immunity -- national floor); KERN-0009 (civil liability disciplines manufacturer conduct across the five categories of preventable harm identified); ENFA-0001 (civil litigation is a structural enforcement mechanism when regulatory enforcement is inadequate or politically blocked). Adversarial review: Gap -- "deceptive marketing to civilians of military-style weapons" requires proof of deception, which is a higher bar than negligent marketing; the category should include reckless marketing (i.e., marketing that creates foreseeable risk of violence regardless of intent to deceive). Loophole -- manufacturers will argue that every civil claim falls outside the five enumerated categories; a catchall provision for "conduct that a reasonable manufacturer should know creates a foreseeable risk of harm to a reasonably identifiable class of persons" would prevent categorical evasion. Unintended consequence -- unlimited class action exposure for defective product design could effectively ban firearm manufacturing through litigation cost; a damages cap or defendant-side fee-shifting for non-meritorious claims may be needed to prevent over-deterrence of lawful manufacturing. Abuse path -- a hostile administration's DOJ could file amicus briefs in PLCAA cases arguing that the five categories should be narrowly interpreted; the statute must specify that the five categories are to be construed broadly in favor of plaintiffs, consistent with ordinary tort law principles.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Sandy Hook families successfully sued Remington under a marketing exception to PLCAA, resulting in a $73 million settlement.<sup><a href="#fn13" id="ref13">[13]</a></sup></p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="GUNS-EXCL-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">GUNS-EXCL-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">ATF Must Conduct Annual Inspections of All Licensed Firearms Dealers</p>
<p class="rule-plain">The Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives (ATF) must inspect every licensed gun dealer every year. Regular inspections catch illegal sales, missing inventory, and record-keeping violations before they fuel more gun violence.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The ATF must conduct an annual compliance inspection of every federally licensed firearm dealer (FFL), including review of acquisition and disposition records, inventory reconciliation, and compliance with background check procedures. Dealers with three or more significant violations within five years must have their licenses revoked; revocation decisions are subject to administrative appeal but may not be stayed pending appeal when there is evidence of ongoing trafficking. The ATF must publish annual dealer compliance statistics by state, including violation rates, revocation rates, and the percentage of crime guns traced to each FFL in the prior year. Any person harmed by a firearm sold or transferred in violation of this section has a private right of action against the FFL for civil damages where ATF inspection records establish a pattern of uncorrected violations.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: Gun Control Act of 1968, 18 U.S.C. § 923(g) (ATF authority to inspect FFL records annually -- but current law limits ATF to one warrantless inspection per year per dealer; this rule makes that annual inspection mandatory and establishes a revocation threshold); 18 U.S.C. § 923(e) (ATF authority to revoke FFL for willful violations -- this rule lowers the "willful" standard to "significant violations" and specifies a three-violation threshold); ATF reported that in recent years fewer than 10% of FFL dealers received any compliance inspection annually (GAO-18-440, 2018). Empirical evidence: GAO-18-440 (2018) found that ATF inspected only 7% of the approximately 130,000 FFL dealers in fiscal year 2017; ATF trace data consistently shows that approximately 5% of dealers account for approximately 90% of crime guns -- these are exactly the dealers that would be identified and revoked under this rule; the current "willful violation" standard for revocation is nearly impossible to meet, allowing dealers with documented compliance failures to retain their licenses indefinitely; states with mandatory dealer inspection programs show significantly lower rates of crime gun diversion per dealer. Enforcement mechanisms: Annual mandatory inspection -- transforms a discretionary ATF function into a statutory obligation; three-significant-violations revocation threshold -- creates a specific and enforceable standard replacing the current nearly-impossible "willful" standard; no-stay of revocation pending appeal when trafficking evidence exists -- prevents dealers from continuing to operate through the multi-year appeal process; public annual statistics by state -- creates political accountability for ATF inspection activity; private right of action -- enforcement against dealers in jurisdictions where ATF enforcement is inadequate. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (federal mandatory inspection creates a uniform national dealer accountability floor); KERN-0009 (mandatory revocation of high-crime-gun-diversion dealers directly reduces the supply of firearms to trafficking networks); ENFA-0001 (annual mandatory inspection rather than 7%-per-year discretionary inspection is a structural enforcement improvement). Adversarial review: Gap -- 130,000 FFLs cannot be inspected annually with ATF's current staffing; the mandatory annual inspection requirement must be paired with a statutory appropriation for ATF inspection staffing or it becomes an unfunded mandate that ATF will be found in structural violation of; a risk-based inspection priority system is needed alongside the mandatory annual requirement. Loophole -- "significant violation" is not defined in the statute; the three-violation threshold is only meaningful if "significant" is defined in a way that cannot be gamed by ATF attorneys arguing that each violation is minor; the statute should define significant violations to include any missing firearm in an inventory reconciliation, any sale to a prohibited person, any failure to conduct a required background check, and any trace request default. Unintended consequence -- annual mandatory inspections may create an administrative burden that discourages small rural dealers (who are not high-diversion dealers) from maintaining their FFL; a risk-based inspection priority that ensures high-diversion dealers are inspected more frequently than low-risk rural dealers would reduce burden on the least problematic licensees. Abuse path -- a hostile administration could define "significant violations" narrowly by regulation, effectively gutting the three-violation threshold; the statute must specify minimum categories of significant violations that ATF may not narrow by rulemaking.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">As of 2021, the ATF was only inspecting dealers approximately once every 14 years on average.<sup><a href="#fn14" id="ref14">[14]</a></sup></p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</section>
<section class="bg-dark on-dark ruled" id="area-research">
<div class="wrap">
<h2 style="color:#7d3c98">Research & Context</h2>
<div class="research-body" style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)"><p>The Second Amendment states: "A well regulated Militia, being necessary to the security of a free State, the right of the people to keep and bear Arms, shall not be infringed." This language has generated two centuries of interpretive conflict. Does "well regulated militia" mean that gun rights are collective (tied to militia service) or individual? What does "well regulated" mean, does it authorize government regulation or simply refer to militias being well-organized? Does "the right to keep and bear Arms" prohibit all regulation or only prohibit complete disarmament?</p>
<p>The Supreme Court's decision in <em>District of Columbia v. Heller</em> (2008) established an individual right to firearm ownership untethered from militia service, striking down D.C.'s handgun ban while acknowledging that this right is "not unlimited" and that "longstanding prohibitions" like bans on concealed carry or possession by felons remain constitutional. <em>McDonald v. City of Chicago</em> (2010) incorporated this right against the states. More recently, <em>New York State Rifle & Pistol Association, Inc. v. Bruen</em> (2022) invalidated New York's "proper cause" requirement for concealed-carry permits, holding that gun regulations must be consistent with "the Nation's historical tradition of firearm regulation." This "history and tradition" test has been criticized for cherry-picking historical examples and making modern regulation difficult by requiring historical analogues to 18th-century laws.</p>
<p>The effect has been to create constitutional uncertainty where basic safety regulations (universal background checks, assault weapon bans, high-capacity magazine limits, red-flag laws) are challenged as unconstitutional, while also leaving undefined what "well regulated" means and whether organized armed groups can be required to maintain transparency and accountability. This policy area seeks to resolve this uncertainty by explicitly affirming government authority to regulate firearms while clarifying that this regulation must be safety-based (not arbitrary prohibition) and that militias can be required to meet "well regulated" standards.</p>
<p>The distinction between lawful firearms and weapons of war is critical. Automatic weapons have been heavily regulated since the National Firearms Act of 1934 and effectively banned for civilian manufacture since 1986. But the proliferation of semi-automatic rifles designed for military use, AR-15 variants, AK-47 variants, and comparable weapons, has enabled mass-casualty attacks while serving no legitimate civilian purpose. These weapons are designed to maximize lethality in combat: high-capacity magazines, rapid fire, and ergonomic features optimized for sustained shooting. They are not traditional hunting rifles or self-defense handguns. Banning "weapons of war" must include not just automatic weapons but semi-automatic civilian versions designed to circumvent regulation. This does not mean banning all semi-automatic firearms, many common handguns and hunting rifles are semi-automatic without being designed for mass casualties. The distinction is design intent and lethality optimization.</p>
<p>Mental health evaluations for gun ownership present difficult tradeoffs. On one hand, individuals experiencing acute mental health crises or expressing intent to harm themselves or others present genuine risk. On the other hand, categorical exclusions based on diagnosis (e.g., banning gun ownership for anyone ever diagnosed with depression, ADHD, autism, or other conditions) are both discriminatory and ineffective. Most people with mental health conditions are not dangerous, and most gun violence is not committed by people with diagnosed mental illness. The solution is narrowly tailored dangerousness-based evaluation: trained professionals can assess whether a specific individual presents imminent risk of harm to themselves or others, but cannot categorically exclude groups based on diagnosis. This prevents discrimination while addressing genuine risk.</p>
<p>Red-flag laws (extreme risk protection orders) allow family members or law enforcement to petition courts to temporarily remove firearms from individuals presenting immediate danger. These laws have been effective in preventing suicides and domestic violence homicides, but they require due process protections to prevent abuse. The standard must be clear evidence of imminent risk, not mere allegation or political targeting. Temporary removal must be time-limited and subject to judicial review.</p>
<p>The regulation of militias is perhaps the most underdeveloped area. The Second Amendment explicitly references "well regulated militia," but neither the Constitution nor federal law clearly defines what this means. Some militias operate as community disaster-response teams, providing legitimate services like search and rescue or emergency shelter coordination. Others are armed groups that reject government oversight, refuse transparency, and train for violent confrontation with federal authorities. The distinction is accountability: regulated militias must maintain membership records, disclose officers and chain of command, carry liability insurance, submit to regular audits, coordinate with state and federal oversight, and follow approved training standards. They can train for disaster relief and work alongside police, fire departments, and the National Guard under clear oversight structures. Private armies and mercenary groups, armed formations that refuse transparency and operate outside democratic accountability, must be explicitly prohibited.</p>
<p>This is not about disarming citizens or eliminating all militias. It is about defining "well regulated" in enforceable terms. A militia that maintains public records, carries insurance, follows safety standards, and coordinates with government authorities for disaster response is meaningfully different from an armed group that refuses all transparency and trains for insurrection. The former can be accommodated; the latter represents a threat to democratic order.</p>
<p>One critical question is the relationship between federal and state regulation. Gun policy has historically been a state-level issue, with federal law establishing minimum standards (background checks for federally licensed dealers, bans on automatic weapons) while states implement stricter or looser requirements. This creates fragmentation where guns purchased in states with weak regulations flow into states with strong regulations, undermining enforcement. Universal background checks, red-flag laws, and assault weapon bans must be national standards to prevent this arbitrage. At the same time, states should retain authority to implement additional protections (waiting periods, training requirements, licensing systems) provided they do not fall below the federal floor.</p>
<p>Another critical question is enforcement. Background checks are only effective if databases are comprehensive and interoperable. Many mass shooters passed background checks because prior offenses or mental health records were not properly reported to federal databases. Training requirements are only effective if training standards are meaningful (not just box-checking exercises). Red-flag laws are only effective if family members and law enforcement know they exist and courts process petitions quickly. Enforcement requires both legal authority and institutional capacity.</p>
<p>This policy area connects to broader policing and accountability reforms. Police should not possess weapons of war either, the militarization of police departments has escalated violence and undermined community trust. Rules JUS-POL-006 (ban police automatic weapons) and JUS-POL-007 (ban police weapons of war) address this. If these weapons are too dangerous for civilian streets, they are too dangerous for routine policing as well. Specialized units may require tactical weapons for specific high-risk situations, but general patrol should not involve military-grade armament.</p>
<p>Finally, this policy area must address the symbolic and political dimensions of gun policy. For many Americans, gun ownership is tied to self-reliance, individual freedom, and resistance to tyranny. For others, gun violence is a public health crisis that demands immediate action. Effective policy must acknowledge both perspectives: regulation is not confiscation, safety training is not infringement, and reducing preventable deaths does not require eliminating all firearms. The goal is a framework that respects legitimate gun ownership while preventing weapons-of-war proliferation, requiring accountability for armed groups, and reducing the tens of thousands of preventable deaths that occur annually from gun violence<sup><a href="#fn2" style="color:var(--accent-color)">[2]</a></sup>.</p></div>
</div>
</section>
